[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Namaste!  (Greetings in the Indian tradition)  to all the chess/Chessable lovers and readers 😊. I am Grandmaster S.P.Sethuraman, and I am back with a bang! This is my second opening course after my successful first one on the “Lifetime Repertoire” of 1. e4 e5, which was a complete package for the Black side. If you have not grabbed it yet, hurry up not to miss the adrenaline-fueled analysis with breathtaking novelties and explanations. I got rave reviews for my first big project, and it was highly enjoyed among the masses. What else does an author need when his students feel excited and receive benefits from the course. In fact, many readers, including some strong players, messaged me by praising the quality of the work and how they used it in online chess to win games. Overwhelmed and honored! Thanks to everyone for their heartwarming feedback, 😍 which brings me to produce my next course.   Guess what? Destiny drags me once again to 1...e5, which has clearly eluded me! The hangover is still not over 😊, but I have a cooked surprise packed in this course. As you might have guessed, we will venture into the city of Gambits :  , the Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit. This idea of creating a course on the Jaenisch Gambit came to my mind when I was watching the Queens Gambit series on Netflix. In the spirit of Beth Harmon, while I was sleeping tight, I got a wild dream. The chess pieces started to move on the ceiling and whispered to me to probe into the Jaenisch Gambit! Bazinga! 😊. Other than the word Gambit, nothing resembles the series, but ideas can pop out from little words.   We will be exclusively dealing only with the Jaenisch Gambit, which will serve as another addition to your repertoire apart from the mainlines in the Spanish. You are always welcome to browse through my first course, which contains a variety of ways to meet the Spanish.  I will be presenting a funkier repertoire, but yet I worked hard to make it theoretically sound as well. I believe that the analysis will talk for itself. }
*

