[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Structure of the Course"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ The course obviously covers the line:   1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  f5!  meaning all of White’s possibilities after that.    This is clearly different from my first course as we will sacrifice the pawn for the initiative from the start of the game. So, the entire course will be like a roller-coaster ride filled with adventures and highly octane variations. We often end up in some positions where we have a pawn less but have decent compensation. There are six chapters in this course. Whenever there are two equally good options, I have delved into it by suggesting an alternative for Black.    For example,   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  f5  4.d3  the positional approach and the most critical one. I have recommended two plans for Black: the one with  4...fxe4  5.dxe4  Nf6  6.O-O  Bc5  by placing the Bishop on a more active square sacrificing the pawn on e5  And the other one being   6...d6  and ...Be7, maintaining the pawn. Both have their own pros and cons, and you will see the different character fights in the opening section.   Chapter 1  will be dealing with all of the sidelines after 3...f5.   Chapter 2  will cover the 4.Nc3, Dyckhoff Variation   Chapter 3  6th move alternatives to the 4.d3 line   Chapter 4  7th move alternatives to the 7.Bxc6 mainline   Chapter 5  mainline with 7.Bxc6   Chapter 6  alternative to the 4.d3 system with 6...d6 and Be7 plan }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Engine Analysis"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ The engines used for the analysis are LC0  (Leela Chess Zero)  and Stockfish 12 NNUE  (Neural Network)  .    So, when analyzing, I thoroughly checked my analysis with both of the engines. They have drastic differences in evaluations due to their contrasting nature, and it is necessary to keep a balance. Especially in this course, I have often come across some areas where Stockfish overestimates an advantage to White as it only calculates the material advantage.  The point being that in Gambits, we sacrifice the pawn too early to gain the initiative.  On the other hand, LC0 thinks that Black is fine, and presents an objective assessment. But not all the time, as Stockfish overpowers LC0 in certain positions. I guess it is here where human evaluation and understanding come into play. I have checked all of the double-edged positions deeply until I am satisfied with the evaluation. In simple terms, the advantage of White is like a Schrodinger's cat. It’s there and yet not there. }
*

