1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are the   4.d3  the Neo line  and   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully. P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is simply worse. }
4. Nc3
{ The old mainline is named the Dyckhoff Variation. The sexiest title ever? I doubt so, but it's funny to hear such opening names. Adds an extra zing to an opening. Upon further research, I also found out that the famous YouTuber IM Levy Rozman has made a video on this opening in his youtube channel GothamChess. Nowadays   5.d3  is more commonly played. }
4... fxe4
{ The logical idea behind ...f5 is to get rid of the e4-pawn and occupy the centre with ...d5. }
5. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Known as the Tartakower Variation. Before   5...d5  The Möhring Variation was heavily played but it is slightly worse after  6.Nxe5!  dxe4  7.Nxc6  So the players slowly drifted to a more sound approach with 5...Nf6. }
6. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Only here   6...gxf6  is not good because of  7.d4  and Black is not in time to consolidate. }
7. Qe2
{ The mainline and the most logical one to attack the e5-pawn instantly. } 7...
Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Standard recapture which sometimes provides the c8-Bishop the a6-square. } 9.
d4 { With the point that   9...exd4  will be met by  10.Bg5 } 9... Qg6
{ Eyeing the g2-pawn. } 10. O-O d6
{ Making way for the monstrous Bishop on c8. } 11. Qc4
{ White attacks the c6-pawn but we can renew communications after... } 11... d5
12. Qc3 { Keeping an eye on the c6-pawn. } 12... exd4 13. Nxd4 c5 14. Nb5
{ 14.Nb3  is met by  14...c4 } 14... O-O { Who cares about c7-pawn? } 15. Nxc7
Rb8 16. Nxd5
{ Who cares about the d5 pawn? This is the attitude we maintain while playing gambit openings. Just kidding, but thanks to our activity we gain enough counterplay for sacrificing our pawns. }
16... Bd6
{ All of our pieces are in commanding positions. White has a couple of options here. }
17. Qd3 Bf5 { No exchange. } 18. Qg3 Bxc2
{ Now we can exchange as we have regained one pawn. } 19. Qxg6 Bxg6
{ The endgame is quite balanced as our activity of the pieces compensates for White's extra pawn. }
20. Re1 Rfd8 { Bringing the Rook to the d-file threatening ...Bxh2+. } 21. h3
Rd7 { Anticipating Bg5 ideas. } 22. b3 Bf7 23. Nc3 c4
{ Exchanging more pawns which will leave the position dead equal after... } 24.
bxc4 Bb4 { Takes a jab at the c3-Knight. } 25. Rb1 Rb6
{ Renewing the threat on the c3-Knight. } 26. c5 Bxc5 27. Bf4 h6
{ and Black comfortably made a draw in Yloenen,O @@StartBracket@@2471@@EndBracket@@-Zemlyanov, S @@StartBracket@@2384@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015. The activity of the bishops simply compensate for White's extra pawn. }
*

