4. Nc3
{ The old mainline is named the Dyckhoff Variation. The sexiest title ever? I doubt so, but it's funny to hear such opening names. Adds an extra zing to an opening. Upon further research, I also found out that the famous YouTuber IM Levy Rozman has made a video on this opening in his youtube channel GothamChess. Nowadays   5.d3  is more commonly played. }
4... fxe4
{ The logical idea behind ...f5 is to get rid of the e4-pawn and occupy the centre with ...d5. }
5. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Known as the Tartakower Variation. Before   5...d5  The Möhring Variation was heavily played but it is slightly worse after  6.Nxe5!  dxe4  7.Nxc6  So the players slowly drifted to a more sound approach with 5...Nf6. }
6. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Only here   6...gxf6  is not good because of  7.d4  and Black is not in time to consolidate. }
7. Qe2
{ The mainline and the most logical one to attack the e5-pawn instantly. } 7...
Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Standard recapture which sometimes provides the c8-Bishop the a6-square. } 9.
Nxe5 Bb7
{ A rare and unexplored option and only played in two correspondence games of Lins.T.   9...Qe6  is heavily played but I found 9...Bb7 more to the spirit of the position as we are planning for O-O-O and to open up the position with ...c5. }
10. O-O
{ 10.d3  O-O-O  11.O-O  anyway transposes to the mainline with 10.O-O. } 10...
O-O-O 11. d4
{ Holding on to the e5-Knight but we can immediately break open with... } 11...
c5 12. c3 { Holding on to the central pawn on d4. } 12... Rhf8
{ Preparing ...d6 to kick the active Knight on e5. It is a difficult move to spot and is prophylactic in nature. The point is that after ...d6, White has always Qg4+ combined with Nd7+ floating in the air. With the Rook on f8, we can interpose with ...Qf5 after ...d6 when White gives a check on g4. }
13. Be3 d6 14. Qg4+
{ 14.Nd3  Qg6  15.Ne1  supporting the g2-pawn  15...Rde8  and Black's activity gives him good counterchances. }
14... Qf5 15. Qxf5+ Rxf5 16. Nd3 c4 { And Black simply fixes the queenside. }
17. Nf4 a5
{ Next, the Black King will come to d7, and once again the two bishops serve us enough compensation as it is not easy for White to advance his pawns on either side. }
