4. Nc3
{ The old mainline is named the Dyckhoff Variation. The sexiest title ever? I doubt so, but it's funny to hear such opening names. Adds an extra zing to an opening. Upon further research, I also found out that the famous YouTuber IM Levy Rozman has made a video on this opening in his youtube channel GothamChess. Nowadays   5.d3  is more commonly played. }
4... fxe4
{ The logical idea behind ...f5 is to get rid of the e4-pawn and occupy the centre with ...d5. }
5. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Known as the Tartakower Variation. Before   5...d5  The Möhring Variation was heavily played but it is slightly worse after  6.Nxe5!  dxe4  7.Nxc6  So the players slowly drifted to a more sound approach with 5...Nf6. }
6. Qe2 { Keeping pressure on the e-file. } 6... d5
{ Our standard action in the centre to free up the position. } 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Of course we take with the pawn to support e5. } 8. O-O Bg4
{ Played in correspondence games as it looks logical to prevent d4 breaks from White. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 { Unpinning, but in turn White weakens his own King. } 10...
Bd6 { A brilliant move sacrificing the piece. } 11. d4 e4 12. Bxc6+
{ 12.gxh5  Qd7  Coming for the h3-pawn and  13.Bxc6  bxc6  will transpose to the mainline. }
12... bxc6 13. gxh5 Qd7 14. Nh2 Qxh3 15. f4 { Renewing communications. } 15...
Kf7 { Adding more fire to the position by bringing the a8-Rook into action. }
16. Kh1 Rhg8 { The a8-Rook is coming to e8. } 17. Be3
{ Blockading the e4-pawn from further advance which helps Black to open up the position but nevertheless Black has great compensation here, after... }
17... Rg3 { The Rook invades. } 18. Rae1 Rag8
{ All of our pieces are ready for an attack. } 19. Rg1 f5
{ was played in the correspondence game of Claridge,J @@StartBracket@@2401@@EndBracket@@ -Nightingale,D @@StartBracket@@2515@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018 which ended in a draw. Black has got enough counterplay thanks to his active pieces. }
*

