{ Our standard action in the centre to free up the position. } 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Of course we take with the pawn to support e5. } 8. d4
{ The standard thrust against Black's centre and we respond back with... } 8...
e4 9. Nh4 Be6 10. O-O Qd6
{ A typical idea preparing O-O-O. The Queen on d6 is better placed than on d7 as it comes under pin there. }
11. f3
{ The entry point to create some play on the Black King but we can already O-O-O here. }
11... O-O-O 12. c3 a6 13. Ba4 f5 { Fortifying the e4-pawn. } 14. fxe4 fxe4 15.
Nf5 Qd7 16. Bg5
{ White's pieces are coming all in but we are in time to create counterplay after... }
16... b5
{ A completely weird kind of position from a Spanish :@@EndBracket@@. Even if one is given a hundred chances to guess the name of the opening from this particular position, I doubt if anyone would succeed. Have never seen such a mess but 'if it works, it works' :@@EndBracket@@. That's the motto of modern chess after all :@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Ne3 { 17.Bxd8  Nxd8  and White will lose one more piece. } 17... bxa4 18.
Qxa6+ Kb8 19. b3 a3 { Keeping the b-file closed. } 20. Qb5+
{ Now White has to force a repetition. } 20... Kc8 { Draw! } *

