8... O-O 9. Nd5 Kh8
{ Moving the King away so that after exchanges on f6, our Rook can come to g8. }
10. Nh4 { The idea is to bring the Queen into play after Bxf6. } 10... Be6 11.
Bxf6 { 11.Nxf6  gxf6  12.Be3  Bb6  is fine for Black. } 11... gxf6 12. Qh5
{ Now you see the point behind Nh4 as White simply controls the f5-square. }
12... Rg8
{ Time for some counterplay, otherwise our position will be doomed to passivity. }
13. c3 Qf8
{ 13...Bxd5  14.exd5  Ne7  15.Bd3  Rg7  and  16.Nf5  White is clearly better.  Instead of 14...Ne7, we can interpose with   14...Rg5  first, not to let White occupy the f5-square and we maintain the equilibrium. Nevertheless the text move 13...Qf8 seems to be simple. }
14. Qf3 Bxd5 15. exd5 Ne7 16. Bd3
{ White is planning to create a bind on the f5-square. } 16... f5
{ In time, before White occupies the f5-square. } 17. Nxf5 Rg5 18. Nh4 Qh6
{ All the pieces are coming in. } 19. g3 Qxh4 20. Qf6+ Kg8
{ And White cannot take the piece back with   21.Qxe7  due to  21...Rxg3  and the Queen is lost. }
21. Kh1 Qh5 22. g4
{ Only move as   22.Qxe7  would lose to  22...Qf3+  23.Kg1  Rg7  and the d3-Bishop is lost. }
22... Qh4 23. Qxe7 Rxg4
{ An equal game with opposite coloured Bishops on the board. } *

