1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are the   4.d3  the Neo line  and   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully. P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is simply worse. }
4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. Of late, this option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4.d3 poses more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. O-O
{ Here Black has two plans. Either to develop the Bishop to c5 or e7 by 6.... d6 followed by 7...Be7. The first option lands the Bishop to a more active square but the drawback is that it loses the e5-pawn. The second is more of strengthening the center but then the Black Bishop on f8 remains passive. We will be looking at both of these options in different chapters. }
6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after   7.Bxc6  which will be dealt with in the 6th chapter. }
7. Bxc6 { The mainline as White gets a free pawn after... } 7... bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ White has grabbed the central pawn but of course we do have some compensation in the form of the bishop pair. }
8... O-O { A couple of moves here are possible. } 9. Nc3 d6 10. Na4
{ Cornering the Bishop on c5. This strange looking move was introduced by Caruana in 2013. }
10... Qe8 { The key move without which Black is worse. } 11. Nd3
{ 11.Nxc5  will be met by  11...Qxe5  and the e4-pawn falls apart when the Knight moves from c5. }
11... Bg4 { Fetching all the pieces to play. } 12. Qe1 Bd4
{ The standard idea to provoke c3 as we witnessed on numerous occasions in this course. }
13. c3 Bb6 14. Nxb6
{ 14.b3?!  Qxe4  15.Qd2  Bf5  was slightly better in Smeets, J @@StartBracket@@2643@@EndBracket@@ -Pruijssers, R @@StartBracket@@2549@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2013. I should mention here that the Dutch Grandmaster Pruijssers is also an expert in this opening as upon analyzing I found many of his games with success. }
14... axb6 15. f3
{ White has secured the extra pawn and also got rid of our Bishop pair. Thanks to the opposite colored Bishops on the board, we can survive the pawn loss. }
15... Be6 { Attacking the a2-pawn. } 16. a3 Bc4 17. Qd1 Qf7
{ Stockfish often overestimates these kinds of positions as clearly better for White as it simply calculates the material advantage. LC0 on the other hand, thinks that Black is fine here as White cannot make much use of the extra pawn with the opposite-colored Bishops. }
18. Re1 Bb3
{ Black simply restricts White's play on the queenside and he enjoys stardom on the light squares. And yes it is a novelty! Hurray!! }
19. Qe2 Nh5 { The Knight eyes for the f4-square. } 20. Be3 c5
{ The pawn formation resembles Rhombus, which restricts White's dark-squared Bishop. Here in this course, we not only learn about chess moves, novelties,  but also Geometry, Polygons, etc, etc...! I doubt of any chess term with Rhombus pawn formation but let us make it popular through this course and spread the word! We are Albert Einstein finding discoveries now and then. Bazinga! }
21. Nc1 { Kicking the Bishop and the bind it has created but after... } 21...
Be6
{ White has no clear plans as he is moving back and forth without clarity. }
22. Qd2 Rad8 23. Nd3 Bb3
{ Once again when the Knight leaves, the Bishop comes back to its original square. The evaluation of this position is a battle between Stockfish and LC0 who give differing opinions. I guess it is here, where human evaluation comes into play and I honestly think this position can be held without any problems. I cannot see any constructive plans from White, nor can Stockfish as well. It keeps claiming advantage for White only because he has an extra pawn. In simple terms, the advantage of White is like a Schrodinger's cat. It's there and yet not there! }
*

