1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are the   4.d3  the Neo line  or   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully. P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is simply worse. }
4. Nc3
{ The old mainline is named the Dyckhoff Variation. The sexiest title ever? I doubt so, but it's funny to hear such opening names. Adds an extra zing to an opening. Upon further research, I also found out that the famous YouTuber IM Levy Rozman has made a video on this opening in his youtube channel GothamChess. Currently,   4.d3  is more commonly played. }
4... fxe4
{ The logical idea behind ...f5 is to get rid of the e4 pawn and occupy the centre with ...d5. }
5. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Known as the Tartakower Variation. Before   5...d5  The Möhring Variation was heavily played but it is slightly worse after  6.Nxe5!  dxe4  7.Nxc6  Because of this, the players slowly drifted to a more sound approach with 5...Nf6. }
6. Ng3
{ To retreat is dubious as it allows Black to march with his pawns jeopardizing the Knights after... }
6... e4 7. Qe2
{ 7.Ng5  will be met by  7...d5  and the Knight on g5 will be kicked next  8.d3  h6  9.Nh3  Bg4!  first provoking the Queen move which will in turn block the c1-Bishop as after  10.Qd2  Bxh3  11.gxh3  Qd7  12.dxe4  O-O-O  Black gains the upper hand.   7.Nh4  will be met by  7...Nd4  and the Bishop on b5 have to go back which is not a good sign. }
7... Qe7 { Unpinning. } 8. Bxc6
{ White cannot move the Knight on f3 as ...Nd4 was on the cards. } 8... bxc6
{ and Black gains the pair of Bishops. Moreover, the Knight on f3 has no proper place to hide and it will be constantly attacked by our pawns. }
9. Nd4 c5 10. Ndf5
{ If   10.Nb5  then  10...d5  supporting the c7-pawn followed by ...c6 next and the Knight again has some issues. }
10... Qe6 { Now the c8-Bishop will come to a6 disturbing the Queen on e2. } 11.
O-O Ba6 12. d3 O-O-O
{ And the pin along the a6-f1 diagonal is quite annoying. Black is better here with the two Bishops and the White Knights are certainly misplaced. }
*

