4. Nc3
{ The old mainline is named the Dyckhoff Variation. The sexiest title ever? I doubt so, but it's funny to hear such opening names. Adds an extra zing to an opening. Upon further research, I also found out that the famous YouTuber IM Levy Rozman has made a video on this opening in his youtube channel GothamChess. Currently,   4.d3  is more commonly played. }
4... fxe4
{ The logical idea behind ...f5 is to get rid of the e4 pawn and occupy the centre with ...d5. }
5. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Known as the Tartakower Variation. Before   5...d5  The Möhring Variation was heavily played but it is slightly worse after  6.Nxe5!  dxe4  7.Nxc6  So the players slowly drifted to a more sound approach with 5...Nf6. }
6. d3
{ Now d3 is too slow as it gives free play for Black in the centre after... }
6... d5 { The centre has to be occupied when given a chance. } 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ I like to capture it with the pawn to maintain the pawn mass in the centre. }
8. d4 { White tries to break the centre. } 8... Qd6
{ Holding on to the centre. } 9. c4
{ Crushing Black's centre, but we are in time to create counterplay after... }
9... dxc4 { Threatening to win the Bishop by ...Qb4+. } 10. O-O Bg4 11. h3 Bd7
{ A weakness has been created on White's camp by provoking h3 and now we come back to unpin our c6-Knight. }
12. Bxc4 { 12.Qe2  O-O-O  and Black has no problems. } 12... exd4 13. Re1+ Be7
14. Bd2
{ On a closer look, White is a pawn down but he has got tremendous activity for the pawn and our pieces are misplaced, with our Queen on d6. Nevertheless, we are not in any danger here and can respond with... }
14... O-O-O 15. Rc1 Kb8
{ and Black is fine here as he is slowly consolidating his position. } *

