6. Qe2 { Keeping pressure on the e-file. } 6... d5
{ Our standard action in the centre to free up the position. } 7. Nxe5
{ Was played in a correspondence game but it hardly works as after... } 7...
dxe4 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxa8 Qxa8
{ The two pieces are worth more than the Rook here as we have better development of our pieces compared to White. }
11. d3 { Trying to challenge the annoying pawn on e4. } 11... Bd6 12. f3
{ 12.dxe4  Qxe4  and Black is slightly better with his active pieces. The text move was the idea behind 11. d3 to win the pawn on e4 but there is a nice resource here after which Black is dominating... }
12... e3
{ A fascinating move and now White will face problems on the e-file as it will become open now once White captures it. }
13. Bxe3 O-O 14. O-O-O a5
{ Followed by ...a4-a3 and White is under trouble as our pieces will slowly penetrate into White's camp. }
