{ Our standard action in the centre to free up the position. } 7. Nxe5
{ Was played in a correspondence game but it hardly works as after... } 7...
dxe4 8. Qc4
{ Threatening mate in one. It looks very obvious but sometimes it is possible to blunder into it. One fine example was the famous game between Deep Fritz 10 vs Kramnik 2006 where Kramnik ran into a mate in 1. So We have to watch like a Hawk when our King is wide open. }
8... Qd6
{ Attacking the active Knight on e5 which creates a lot of play around our King. }
9. Nf7 Qe6
{ We will lose the Rook now but the h8-Knight is sealed once it takes the Rook. We already have an extra piece, so more or less it will end up where we will have two pieces for the Rook. }
10. Nxh8 a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qc3
{ Dimov,I @@StartBracket@@2457@@EndBracket@@-Rebord,M @@StartBracket@@2531@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2007 }
12... Nd5
{ An improvement over the correspondence game, harassing the Queen and we are better after... }
13. Qg3 Qf6 { With ...Bd6 to follow and White's position is collapsing. } *

