1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are   4.d3  the Neo line  and   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully.    P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is dubious. }
4. Nc3
{ The old mainline is named the Dyckhoff Variation. The sexiest title ever? I doubt so, but it's funny to hear such opening names. Adds an extra zing to an opening. Upon further research, I also found out that the famous YouTuber IM Levy Rozman has made a video on this opening in his youtube channel GothamChess. Currently,   4.d3  is more commonly played. }
4... fxe4
{ The logical idea behind ...f5 is to get rid of the e4 pawn and occupy the centre with ...d5. }
5. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Known as the Tartakower Variation. Before   5...d5  The Möhring Variation was heavily played but it is slightly worse after  6.Nxe5!  dxe4  7.Nxc6  So the players slowly drifted to a more sound approach with 5...Nf6. }
6. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Only here   6...gxf6  is not good because of  7.d4  and Black is not in time to consolidate. }
7. Qe2
{ The mainline and the most logical one to attack the e5-pawn instantly. } 7...
Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Standard recapture which sometimes provides the c8-Bishop with access to the a6-square. }
9. Nxe5 Bb7
{ A rare and unexplored option and only played in two Correspondence games of Lins.T.   9...Qe6  is heavily played but I found 9...Bb7 more to the spirit of the position as we are planning for O-O-O and to open up the position with ...c5. }
10. O-O
{ 10.d3  O-O-O  11.O-O  anyway transposes back to the mainline here with 10.O-O. }
10... O-O-O 11. d3 Rde8
{ Black has two options: either to bring the h8-Rook or the d8-Rook to e8 to create pressure on the e-file. The text move is precise as in this particular position Black needs the other Rook to be on h8 so that he can create some counter chances with ...h5. That's the subtle point here. }
12. Bd2 Bd6
{ 12...Qf5  is interesting as well, threatening ...Bf6 and ...d6 to trap the Knight on e5. Play will continue after  13.Nc4  c5  opening the diagonal for the b7-Bishop  14.Rfe1  doubling on the e-file so that we cannot move the Bishop now. This is due to the fact that White can take twice on e8 but we have a strong resource after  14...Ref8!  with the idea that the e7 piece cannot be taken because of the f2-pawn hanging.  15.Qf1  and now White is planning to take the piece on e7  15...Bh4  with good counterplay. }
13. f4 g5 { Destroying the defender which holds the e5-Knight. } 14. Rae1 gxf4
15. Bxf4 h5
{ A useful advance to stir up White's position by rolling the pawn to create an attack. }
16. Qd2 Qg7
{ Threatening now to take the piece on e5 as we have moved away from the pin. }
17. Nc4 Bxf4 18. Rxf4 c5 { The monstrous Bishop is opened up. } 19. Rf2
{ Defending the g2-pawn. } 19... d6 20. c3 Kb8 21. Ne3 Qg6
{ With a lot of play left as in the correspondence game of Krauss, H @@StartBracket@@2396@@EndBracket@@-Lins, T @@StartBracket@@2462@@EndBracket@@ GER email 2019. Black has sufficient compensation as the g-file is opened which makes the White King uncomfortable especially with the scintillating Bishop on b7. }
