7. Qe2
{ The mainline and the most logical one to attack the e5-pawn instantly. } 7...
Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Standard recapture which sometimes provides the c8-Bishop with access to the a6-square. }
9. Nxe5 Bb7
{ A rare and unexplored option and only played in two Correspondence games of Lins.T.   9...Qe6  is heavily played but I found 9...Bb7 more to the spirit of the position as we are planning for O-O-O and to open up the position with ...c5. }
10. O-O
{ 10.d3  O-O-O  11.O-O  anyway transposes back to the mainline here with 10.O-O. }
10... O-O-O 11. d4
{ Holding on to the e5-Knight but we can immediately break open with... } 11...
c5 12. Be3 Rhe8 { Threatening ...d6 next and the e-file is under fire. } 13. c3
{ Safeguarding the centre. } 13... Ba6 14. Nc4
{ If White interposes with his Knight then he adds one more piece into this annoying pin. }
14... Qe6
{ So we first implant our Queen to e6 so that if White supports the Knight with   15.b3  then we win the Knight on c4 by  15...d5    A direct   14...d5  will be met by  15.Qg4+ }
15. d5 { Thanks to this tactics, White survives. } 15... Qxd5 16. Nb6+ axb6 17.
Qxa6+ Qb7 18. Qd3 g6 { The h7-pawn was attacked. } 19. a4 d5
{ In time, before White marches ahead with his pawn on the a-file. } 20. a5 b5
{ And the central pawn mass simply sabotages White's attack if any. } 21. a6
Qc6
{ And if   22.Ra5  c4  23.Qd4  Bf6  24.Qa7  we have the coldblooded  24...Kd7 !  and White's Queen has no proper squares. }
