4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. This option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4. d3 gives more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. Nc3
{ A slight inaccuracy in the move order to develop the Knight before castling as now we can counter it with ... }
6... Bb4
{ The key point exploiting the premature development of the Knight to c3. Now the e4-pawn comes under pressure. }
7. Bg5
{ White in turn pins the f6-Knight but now the c3-Knight will be shattered by... }
7... Bxc3+ { Weakening the pawn structure of White. } 8. bxc3 d6 9. O-O O-O
{ And Black is slightly better because of the doubled c-pawns and lack of coordination in White's pawn structure. }
