4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. This option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4. d3 gives more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. Nc3
{ A slight inaccuracy in the move order to develop the Knight before castling as now we can counter it with ... }
6... Bb4
{ The key point exploiting the premature development of the Knight to c3. Now the e4-pawn comes under pressure. }
7. Bd2
{ White tries to prevent the shattering of pawn structure after ...Bxc3 by placing his Bishop to d2. Now White could take with the Bishop rather than the pawn. }
7... d6
{ The threat right now is that we will take on c3 and the e4-pawn is lost. } 8.
Qe2 { Supporting the pawn on e4. } 8... O-O 9. Bxc6 Bxc3
{ An important intermezzo as   9...bxc6 ?  would be a blunder because of  10.Qc4+  and we lose the Bishop on b4. }
10. Bxc3 bxc6 11. Qc4+
{ White can capture the pawn on c6 but the light-squared Bishop serves us good compensation after... }
11... Kh8 12. Qxc6 Bd7 13. Qc4 Rb8
{ And White cannot castle immediately because of   14.O-O?  14...Bb5  and he will lose the exchange. So, Black has clear compensation for the pawn in this position. }
