4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. Qd3
{ Played in some online games as well recently. The idea is simply to protect the e4-pawn and develop the Knight to c3. Moreover, the Queen will land on c4 sometimes to prevent us from castling and also exert pressure on the c6-Knight once we commit to the d6 advance. }
6... Bb4+
{ Once again, our standard intermediate move creates a ruckus in White's camp as now he will have to decide how to sabotage the check. Just to add that the exchange of the dark-squared Bishops is in Black's favor as there is no more Bg5 business. }
7. Nbd2
{ If White interposes with the Knight, with the aim of c3-b4 then I found a remarkable novelty here with... }
7... a5
{ Against the idea of a c3-b4 advance. Black now secures the b4-Bishop and makes more space for it to breathe. }
8. O-O
{ 8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Nxe5  Qe7  10.f4  Ba6  and the two Bishops create a lot of play. Especially with the Queen placed on d3, it is not advisable to go for the pawn grab here. }
8... Qe7 { Supporting the e5-pawn. } 9. Nc4 O-O 10. Bxc6
{ 10.Bg5  d6  11.Ne3  Be6  12.Bc4  h6  and Black has consolidated his position with no weaknesses. With 10.Bxc6, White aims to capture the e5-pawn but as always we have good compensation in the form of the Bishop pair. }
10... bxc6 11. a3 Bc5 12. Ncxe5 d6 13. Nxc6 Qe8
{ Disturbing the Knight first as if we take on e4 with   13...Qxe4  then  14.Qxe4  Nxe4  15.Ne7+  and White is clearly better with the simple fact that he gets rid of the Bishop pair and has an extra pawn. }
14. Ncd4 Ba6
{ One more intermezzo before taking on e4. Black is totally fine here. } *

