{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. This option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4. d3 gives more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. O-O
{ Here Black has two plans. Either to develop the Bishop to c5 or e7 by 6.... d6 followed by 7...Be7. The first option lands the Bishop to a more active square but the drawback is that it loses the e5-pawn. The second is more of strengthening the center but then the Black Bishop on f8 remains passive. We will be looking at both of these options in different chapters. }
6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after   7.Bxc6  which will be dealt with in the 6th chapter. }
7. Qd3
{ with the idea of Qc4+ if Black castles. The Queen is better placed on d3 rather than on e2 which allows ...Nd4 as discussed in the 7.Qe2 variant. }
7... d6
{ Supporting the e5-pawn and the c5-Bishop. It also makes way for the c8-Bishop. }
8. Qc4
{ Looks very logical to prevent the c8-Bishop from developing to e6 and preventing O-O as well. This was the topical line played heavily during the mid-2000s by the elite players. }
8... Bd7 { The idea is...Qe7 followed by long castle. } 9. Bxc6
{ White can try for a pawn grab after.. } 9... Bxc6 10. Nxe5 Bxf2+
{ But this intermediate move regains the pawn for us. Of course, our King is still wide open but with fewer pieces on the board it is not easy for White to exploit it. Next, we will bring our Queen to stabilize the position. }
11. Rxf2 dxe5 12. Nc3
{ 12.Bg5  Qd1+  13.Rf1  Qg4  14.Bxf6  gxf6  and Black is fine here as the e4-pawn is under attack. }
12... Qe7 { Preparing O-O-O. } 13. Be3
{ 13.Bg5  O-O-O  14.Nd5  Bxd5  15.exd5  Qd6  with an equal position. The point of the text move 13.Be3 is that it keeps an eye on the a7-pawn. This makes O-O-O difficult now as then the a7-pawn falls apart but we have.... }
13... Qf7 { Challenging the Queen on c4. } 14. Qc5
{ Once again prevents castle on both sides but Black can always keep interposing with the Queen leading to a draw after.. }
14... Qe7 { And White is lacking choices to continue the game. } *

