{ Looks very logical to prevent the c8-Bishop from developing to e6 and preventing O-O as well. This was the topical line played heavily during the mid-2000s by the elite players. }
8... Bd7 { The idea is...Qe7 followed by long castle. } 9. Nc3 Qe7
{ Preparing O-O-O and was heavily played in 2008 by Radjabov whose main repertoire was the Jaenisch at that time. White players were constantly trying to prove an edge but Radjabov was holding his own most of the time. The opening still stands the test of time. }
10. Nd5 { Continuing the plan of Nc3 but leads to massive exchanges after... }
10... Nxd5 11. exd5
{ 11.Qxd5  Qe6  is just equal as we chase the active Queen on d5. } 11... Nd4
12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. a4
{ Expanding on the queenside to create more space and also with a sneaky threat of trapping the d4-Bishop with c3.   14...Bc5  will be met by  15.b4  and   14...Bb6  with  15.a5  So we have to be careful here not to blunder the Bishop. }
14... a6
{ Important to play a6 and not   14...a5  as after  15.Be3  Bxe3  16.fxe3  we cannot go for  16...O-O-O?!  because of  17.b4  and White breaks open the position. }
