{ On a closer look, all the minor pieces are exchanged. White in the mid-2000s was claiming that due to the control over the f-file he obtains a slight edge but with very few pieces on the board. It isn't a major thing and Black can easily neutralize after... }
16... O-O-O 17. Rf2
{ Planning to double the Rook on the f-file with the intention to come to f7. }
17... Rdf8
{ Changing one pair of Rooks before White takes absolute control over the f-file. Nothing wrong with placing the h8-Rook to f8 but the plus point of placing the d-Rook to f8, is that Black's h7-pawn is well protected when White plays Qe4. }
18. Raf1 Rxf2 19. Rxf2 Kb8
{ And Black has no problems in the game of Topalov-Radjabov 2008 as White cannot make use of the control on the f-file with minimal pieces left on the board. }
20. b3 Qe7 { Preparing ...Rf8. } 21. Qe4 g6
{ is necessary to bring the Rook on h8 to f8. } 22. Qf3
{ White takes control over the f-file before Black challenges with ...Rf8. The big question is, 'What is next?'. }
22... Rc8 { Sometime in the future we can break open with ...c6. } 23. Rf1 c6
{ Now we see the point of ...Rc8. } 24. c4 e4 25. Qd1 Qe5 { Centralization! }
26. dxc6 Rxc6
{ Black gains sufficient activity and it was draw in the correspondence game of Vetter,G @@StartBracket@@2394@@EndBracket@@-Voetter,H @@StartBracket@@2380@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2010. }
