{ 9.Nc3  Bd7  is a direct transposition to 8...Bd7 9. Nc3 Qe7 line as   9...Be6  would be a mistake due to  10.Nd5  and we cannot capture the Knight on d5 with  10...Nxd5 ?  due to  11.exd5  and we lose a piece. }
9... bxc6 10. b4 Be6
{ More or less, the occurring variations are forced as White is trying to get the c6-pawn and Black is tactically solving his problems. }
11. Qa6 Bb6 12. a4 { With the threat of a5. } 12... O-O 13. a5 Bd4 14. Nxd4
exd4 15. Nd2
{ 15.Qxc6  is highly dangerous after  15...Ng4  as White's kingside is collapsing. }
15... Nh5
{ The Knight is shifted towards the kingside for attack as the White Queen is far from reach. }
16. Qxc6 Nf4 17. Kh1
{ 17.Nf3  Bd7  18.Qc4  Be6  and surprisingly it is a repetition as White cannot take on d4 due to Ne2+. Also, White has no proper squares for the Queen. }
17... Qg5 { Threatening mate on g2. } 18. Rg1 Ne2 19. Rf1 Nf4
{ With a repetition once again. } *

