{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. O-O
{ Here Black has two plans. Either to develop the Bishop to c5 or e7 by 6.... d6 followed by 7...Be7. The first option lands the Bishop to a more active square but the drawback is that it loses the e5-pawn. The second is more of strengthening the center but then the Black Bishop on f8 remains passive. We will be looking at both of these options in different chapters. }
6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after   7.Bxc6  which will be dealt with in the 6th chapter. }
7. Nc3 d6 8. Bg5
{ 8.Qd3  will transpose to 7.Qd3 line. The text move is logical as White's whole idea of Nc3 is to plant his Bishop to g5 and Knight to d5, to exert pressure on our f6-Knight. }
8... O-O 9. Nd5 Kh8
{ Moving the King away so that after exchanges on f6, our Rook can come to g8. }
10. c3
{ Was played by the legendary players who consistently prove that age is just a number! Pretty sure you guys must have guessed by now of who it is Anand vs Ivanchuk 2011. }
10... Ne7 { The Knight on c6 has no scope so we reroute it to the kingside. }
11. Nxf6 gxf6 12. Be3
{ 12.Bh6  Rg8  and it is White who has to be careful now with the g-file under fire. }
12... Bxe3 13. fxe3 d5
{ is an improvement over the aformentioned game clarifying matters in the centre. }
14. Nh4 { 14.exd5  Qxd5  will make Black comfortable. } 14... dxe4 15. Qxd8
Rxd8 16. Rxf6 Nd5
{ And Black is fine here with the active Knight on d5 which compensates for the doubled e-pawns. }
*

