6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after   7.Bxc6  which will be dealt with in the 6th chapter. }
7. Bg5 { Pinning the Knight on f6 to reduce the pressure on e4-pawn. } 7... h6
{ Asking a question to the Bishop immediately. } 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nc3
{ The Knight is heading to d5. } 9... Ne7
{ Logical to prevent the Nd5 jump from White. } 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Next ...c6 is threatened. } 12. Rad1 Ke7
{ Renewing the threat of ...c6 as the Bishop on d6 has to be protected. Once again, Black can afford to move the King as his centre is solid. As ...c6 is coming, White has to slowly go back with his pieces. }
13. Bc4 Rb8
{ A strong move threatening ...b5 as Bxb5 will lose the piece to ...c6. So, White has to make a decision with his c4-Bishop and cannot create active play. }
