Nf6 6. O-O
{ Here Black has two plans. Either to develop the Bishop to c5 or e7 by 6.... d6 followed by 7...Be7. The first option lands the Bishop to a more active square but the drawback is that it loses the e5-pawn. The second is more of strengthening the center but then the Black Bishop on f8 remains passive. We will be looking at both of these options in different chapters. }
6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after }
7. Bxc6 { The mainline as White gets a free pawn after.. } 7... bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ White has grabbed the central pawn but of course we do have some compensation in the form of the Bishop pair. }
8... O-O { A couple of moves here are possible. } 9. Nd2
