4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. This option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4. d3 gives more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. O-O
{ Here Black has two plans. Either to develop the Bishop to c5 or e7 by 6.... d6 followed by 7...Be7. The first option lands the Bishop to a more active square but the drawback is that it loses the e5-pawn. The second is more of strengthening the center but then the Black Bishop on f8 remains passive. We will be looking at both of these options in different chapters. }
6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after }
7. Bxc6 { The mainline as White gets a free pawn after.. } 7... bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ White has grabbed the central pawn but of course we do have some compensation in the form of the Bishop pair. }
8... O-O { A couple of moves here are possible. } 9. Nc3 d6 10. Na4
{ Cornering the Bishop on c5. This strange looking move was introduced by Caruana in 2013. }
10... Qe8 { The key move without which Black is worse. } 11. Nd3
{ 11.Nxc5  will be met by  11...Qxe5  and the e4-pawn falls apart when the Knight moves from c5. }
11... Bg4 { Fetching all the pieces to play. } 12. Qe1 Bd4
{ The standard idea to provoke c3 as we witnessed on numerous occasions in this course. }
13. c3 Bb6 14. h3 { Played heavily in correspondence games. } 14... Bc8
{ We can as well place the Bishop on e6, but the point of going back all the way to c8 is to maintain the pressure on the e4-pawn. }
15. e5 { 15.Nxb6  axb6  16.e5  transposes to the text with 15.e5. } 15... dxe5
16. Nxe5 { 16.Nxb6  axb6  17.Nxe5  Qh5  transposes simply. } 16... Qh5 17. Nxb6
axb6
{ White has an extra pawn but like in most of the cases in this opening, the opposite-colored Bishops on the board come to the rescue. The opposite-colored Bishops help Black hold and increase the drawing tendency. Next on the cards is ...Ba6. }
18. b3 Re8 19. f4 Nd7 { Changing the active Knight on e5. } 20. a4 Nxe5 21.
fxe5 Ba6 22. c4 Qxe5 23. Bf4 Qd4+
{ was played in the correspondence game of Matveeva,M  @@StartBracket@@2501@@EndBracket@@ -Williamson,H @@StartBracket@@2514@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018 , where after some moves, the game ended in a draw. }
*

