[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are   4.d3  the Neo line  and   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully.    P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is dubious. }
4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. This option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4. d3 gives more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4
{ White was already threatening to take on f5, so this looks logical. } 5. dxe4
Nf6 6. O-O
{ Here Black has two plans. Either to develop the Bishop to c5 or e7 by 6.... d6 followed by 7...Be7. The first option lands the Bishop to a more active square but the drawback is that it loses the e5-pawn. The second is more of strengthening the center but then the Black Bishop on f8 remains passive. We will be looking at both of these options in different chapters. }
6... Bc5
{ As destiny chooses it, my repertoire is once again filled with the Bishop landing on c5. Perhaps you will have a clue of what I am talking about if you have checked my first Chessable course: Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1. e4 e5 with the Black side. Black develops the Bishop to c5, to a more active square to put pressure on the f2-pawn followed by O-O. Of course, the drawback is that we lose the e5-pawn after }
7. Bxc6 { The mainline as White gets a free pawn after.. } 7... bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ White has grabbed the central pawn but of course we do have some compensation in the form of the Bishop pair. }
8... O-O { A couple of moves here are possible. } 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nd3 Bd4
{ Kicking the c3-Knight first so that the e4-pawn will come under attack. } 11.
Qe1 Qe8
{ Adding more pressure on the e4-pawn and White is now unable to protect it anymore. }
12. Be3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Qxe4
{ Taking with the Queen is necessary as if we take with the Knight as in   13...Nxe4  14.Qc4+  d5  15.Qa4  followed by Re1 and White is on top. Hence 13...Qxe4 is important. Though the material is equal now, we have some problems with our c6-pawn, so we have to deal with it carefully. There are two ways for White here, Rfe1 and Rae1 to harass the Queen on e4 which holds the c6-pawn. }
14. Rae1 Qa4
{ The only move by which Black does not end up worse. White was threatening to move the e3-Bishop posing discovered threats on the Queen and we have to not lose contact over the c6-pawn. }
15. b3 Nd5 { Deflecting the Queen from c3 which attacks our c6-pawn. } 16. Qb2
Qg4 { The Queen oscillates like a pendulum! } 17. c4 Bf5
{ You attack, I also attack! } 18. f3 Qg6 19. Ne5 dxe5 20. cxd5 Bd3
{ Activating the Bishop. } 21. Rf2 e4
{ and the position is equal with the opposite coloured Bishops. } *

