{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are   4.d3  the Neo line  and   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully.    P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is dubious. }
4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. Of late this option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4 d3 posses more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ This is a different approach altogether as we place the Bishop on e7 here compared to the 6...Bc5 line. By this approach, we don't lose the e5-pawn and the center remains intact. The drawback is that the Bishop on e7 is passively placed. White can often try to exploit the c4-g8 diagonal as our play is a bit slow compared to the 6... Bc5 line. }
7. Qd3
{ Like discussed in the 7.Qe2 variation, the White Queen aims to go to c4 next. Unlike in 7.Qe2, White does not come under the ...Bg4 pin here. }
7... a6 { Disturbing the Bishop. } 8. Ba4 Be7 { Preparing ...O-O. } 9. Nc3 Bd7
{ 9...O-O  will be met by  10.Qc4  Although Black definitively has clear compensation for the pawn, I found the text move to be simpler. }
10. Bb3 Na5 { Chasing the Bishop as always. } 11. Ng5 Nxb3 12. Qc4
{ A sneaky intermediate move which threatens Qf7 mate. } 12... Rf8
{ Only move to safeguard the f7 spot. } 13. Qxb3 h6 14. Ne6 Bxe6
{ transposes tothis line. } 15. Qxe6 Qd7
{ Followed by ...O-O-O and we don't have any problems with our King. } *

