{ This is a different approach altogether as we place the Bishop on e7 here compared to the 6...Bc5 line. By this approach, we don't lose the e5-pawn and the center remains intact. The drawback is that the Bishop on e7 is passively placed. White can often try to exploit the c4-g8 diagonal as our play is a bit slow compared to the 6... Bc5 line. }
7. Bc4
{ The critical option exploiting the drawback of our missing pawn on f7. } 7...
Bg4
{ Creating counter chances. The idea is to develop the Queen followed by O-O-O as soon as possible.   7...Na5  now is bit slow as after  8.Be2  Be7  White has time to shove the Knight away by  9.b4  Nc6  10.b5  followed by Bc4 with a promising advantage. }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Qd3
{ White moves out from the pin and this option looks logical. } 9... Nd7
{ Eureka! Interesting novelty to harass the d3-Queen. } 10. Nc3
{ Stockfish once again overestimates White's position. It claims to be a slight advantage for White of over 0.50. If we talk about computer terms, LC0 gives a balanced evaluation for Black as something like 0.19. There is a drastic contrast opinion by both the engines. In such cases, we can only get to a conclusion after in-depth analysis. Let us dive into it. }
10... Be7 11. g4 { is interesting but gives Black some play after... } 11...
Nc5 12. Qe2 Bg6 13. Rb1 a5
{ prevents b4 and Black seals his Knight on c5 creating pressure on the e4-pawn. }
