{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. Of late this option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4 d3 posses more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ This is a different approach altogether as we place the Bishop on e7 here compared to the 6...Bc5 line. By this approach, we don't lose the e5-pawn and the center remains intact. The drawback is that the Bishop on e7 is passively placed. White can often try to exploit the c4-g8 diagonal as our play is a bit slow compared to the 6... Bc5 line. }
7. Bc4
{ The critical option exploiting the drawback of our missing pawn on f7. } 7...
Bg4
{ Creating counter chances. The idea is to develop the Queen followed by O-O-O as soon as possible.   7...Na5  now is bit slow as after  8.Be2  Be7  White has time to shove the Knight away by  9.b4  Nc6  10.b5  followed by Bc4 with a promising advantage. }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Qd3
{ White moves out from the pin and this option looks logical. } 9... Nd7
{ Eureka! Interesting novelty to harass the d3-Queen. } 10. Nc3
{ Stockfish once again overestimates White's position. It claims to be a slight advantage for White of over 0.50. If we talk about computer terms, LC0 gives a balanced evaluation for Black as something like 0.19. There is a drastic contrast opinion by both the engines. In such cases, we can only get to a conclusion after in-depth analysis. Let us dive into it. }
10... Be7 11. Nd5 { Logical to cruise in with the Knight. } 11... Nc5 12. Qa3
{ 12.Qe3  Bf7  and Black consolidates. The point of Qa3 is that after Whites b4-b5 advance, it takes away the a5 square for the c6-Knight. }
12... Ne6
{ is necessary as   12...Bf7  here would lead to  13.b4  Ne6  14.b5  and Black lacks the a5 square for his c6-Knight due to the placement of the Queen on a3. }
13. b4 O-O
{ Black calmly castles albeit the light squares under fire. The point is that with the Bishop on h5, we are threatening now to take on f3. }
14. Nxc7
{ 14.Nxe7  Qxe7  15.Ng5  and we are in time to save our Knight by  15...Nd4 }
14... Qxc7 15. Bxe6+ Kh8
{ We have lost a pawn but we have definitively consolidated the position of our king. White is under pressure now with his pawns scattered on the queenside. }
16. Bg4 Bxg4 17. hxg4 d5
{ The standard sacrifice which always comes out of the blue. } 18. exd5 e4
{ And if the White Knight moves, then our c6-Knight will land on d4 creating counterplay. }
19. dxc6 exf3 { The position is balanced after } 20. gxf3 Qxc6
{ as White's pawns are scattered. } *

