{ Protecting the e4-pawn and also now Ne6 is threatened. } 11... Nd4
{ The only way to safeguard the e6 square and as well our Knight gains activity. }
12. f4 c6 { Controlling the central square on d5. } 13. f5
{ At first glance, looks really scary for Black with the King in the centre and the light squares being extremely vulnerable. But, we are in time to save ourselves after... }
13... h6 { The key point, without which we are simply lost. } 14. fxg6 hxg5
{ And Black gains play on the h-file. } 15. Bf7+
{ 15.Kg2  will be met by  15...d5 } 15... Kd7 16. Kg2 Kc7
{ The Majesty walks! Next ...Rc8 followed by ...Kb8 and the King reached its destination. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alternative: 4.d3 fxe4 5.dxe4 Nf6 6.O-O d6 & Be7 plan"]
[Black "4.d3 with 6...d6 7.Bc4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann-Jaenisch Gambit 3... f5!?, is a sharp line in which Black plays for a Kingside attack, frequently sacrificing one or two pawns. This system is used to upset Ruy Lopez  (Spanish)  players and was explored in 1847 by the Finnish player Carl Jaenisch, but adopted later by the German chess player Adolf Schliemann. The most common responses for White to 3... f5!? are   4.d3  the Neo line  and   4.Nc3  the Old mainline.  This line is considered to be a decent practical weapon. The drawback is that Black pushes the f-pawn to f5 and seriously weakens the squares around his King. The Jaenisch Gambit is one of the most aggressive systems that Black can play against the Ruy Lopez. This closely resembles a reverse Vienna Gambit or King's Gambit as Black offers an early pawn.    One of the main advantages of Jaenisch Gambit is the element of surprise. By immediately sidestepping the main lines of the Ruy Lopez, you are going to take your opponent out of his preparation and directly into yours guaranteeing you a psychological advantage in the first stage of the game. It is also very uncomfortable for most Ruy Lopez players to face such a dynamic response from Black. Many Spanish Game players are more inclined to a quieter game full of positional maneuvering, not the crazy tactical complications that commonly arise in the Jaenisch Gambit.    If you are looking for dynamism with the black pieces against the Ruy Lopez, the Jaenisch Gambit is the solution you have been looking for! Special mentions to the Azeri Grandmaster Teimour Radjabov, who has a fair deal in popularising this opening in the mid-2000s. He singlehandedly used this system holding on to his grounds against the topmost players successfully.    P.S- Fun Fact - In the English opening, 1. c4 b5 ?!!??! is also called Jaenisch Gambit. The gambit is also named after Carl Jaenisch, who pioneered both of these openings.  Here Black obtains no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and is dubious. }
4. d3
{ A calm move, just holding on to the central pawn on e4. Of late this option has been the trend against the Jaenisch and remains an acid test for Black. Unlike the forced variations arising after 4.Nc3, 4 d3 posses more of a positional character. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ This is a different approach altogether as we place the Bishop on e7 here compared to the 6...Bc5 line. By this approach, we don't lose the e5-pawn and the center remains intact. The drawback is that the Bishop on e7 is passively placed. White can often try to exploit the c4-g8 diagonal as our play is a bit slow compared to the 6... Bc5 line. }
7. Bc4
{ The critical option exploiting the drawback of our missing pawn on f7. } 7...
Bg4
{ Creating counter chances. The idea is to develop the Queen followed by O-O-O as soon as possible.   7...Na5  now is bit slow as after  8.Be2  Be7  White has time to shove the Knight away by  9.b4  Nc6  10.b5  followed by Bc4 with a promising advantage. }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3
{ The mainline which was also played in the game of Caruana-Carlsen, St.Louis 2019. }
9... Be7
{ I like this move over   9...Qd7  which is heavily played as then White can place his Queen to d3 without having to worry about ...Nd7 ideas. So I prefer the more subtle text move. }
10. g4 { 10.Qd3  Nd7  transposes to 9.Qd3 line. } 10... Bg6 11. Ng5
{ Protecting the e4-pawn and also now Ne6 is threatened. } 11... Nd4
{ The only way to safeguard the e6 square and as well our Knight gains activity. }
12. f4 c6 { Controlling the central square on d5. } 13. f5
{ At first glance, looks really scary for Black with the King in the centre and the light squares being extremely vulnerable. But, we are in time to save ourselves after... }
13... h6 { The key point, without which we are simply lost. } 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15.
Qxf3 Bf7 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7
{ Followed by ...Re8 and ...Kg8. Also, ideas like ...d5 are floating in the air. For the first time, Stockfish agrees that Black is doing fine here. So, lets end on a happy note! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Ivanchuk, Vassily, (Sao Paulo 2011)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now we will see a fascinating battle between the two evergreen legends who consistently prove that age is just a number :@@EndBracket@@. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ One can never predict Chucky's opening choices :@@EndBracket@@. I have played two games against him and I was also not successful in guessing what he will play. And here we see the Jaenisch Gambit. This must have been a shocker for Vishy as it is a rare guest at the top level. }
4. d3
{ A solid and a critical approach against the Jaenisch.   4.Nc3  fxe4  5.Nxe4  Nf6  is discussed in the opening chapters. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6
{ There are so many options here for White as we witnessed in the opening files. Let us stick to the most natural move played in the game after }
6. O-O Bc5 { The Bishop is actively placed on c5. } 7. Nc3
{ White develops his Knight to c3 where it is ideally placed as it protects the e4-pawn. The Knight also plans to invade the d5-square and create pressure on the f6-Knight after Bg5 ideas. }
7... O-O 8. Bg5 { The logical idea behind Nc3. } 8... d6
{ Protecting the central pawn on e5 and now the c8-Bishop is coming to play. }
9. Nd5
{ For the moment, White's pieces are cruising through our camp but nevertheless, we are solid and not easy to break. }
9... Kh8 { A standard king retreat to secure it from all sorts of threats. }
10. c3
{ 10.Nh4  is one of the critical moves advocated by the well known theoretician Parimarjan Negi. This move is dealt with exclusively in the openings section. }
10... Ne7
{ Blocking the pin along the g5-d8 diagonal and now our Knight on e7 will land to g6. The knight slowly comes to the kingside which can act as both a defensive and attacking piece. }
11. Nxf6 gxf6 12. Be3
{ White exchanges the active Bishop on c5. By this exchange, he can open up the f-file for his f1-Rook to put pressure on our backward pawn on f6. The drawback is that he doubles his e-pawn. }
12... Bxe3 13. fxe3 Ng6
{ A practical response by Chucky as the novelty and the consequences after 13...d5 is difficult to judge over the board especially if you are not well prepared. The text move is also equally possible but 13...d5 is more forcing as it clarifies the matter in the center quickly leading to equal play.   13...d5 !  is the strong novelty recommended by me in the opening chapter.  For more details, please hop on to theopening section. Let us stick to the move played in the game. }
14. Nd2
{ 14.Bd3 !  is more accurate stopping all sorts of freeing breaks for Black like ...f5 and ...d5.  14...Qd7  A subtle Queen maneuver to bring the Queen to the kingside.   14...d5   14...f5  loses to  15.exf5  Bxf5  and  16.Ne5  trick.  15.exd5  Qxd5  16.Bxg6  The key point behind 14. Bd3.  16...Qxd1  17.Raxd1  hxg6  18.Nxe5  ±  and White has an extra pawn, thanks to the pin.  15.Rf2  Qg7  16.Nd2  +=  White has a microscopic edge as we cannot free our position with breaks such as ...d5 and ...f5. That is the reason I recommend this strong novelty on move 13 with ...d5 immediately. If White restricts our ideas of breaking the game wide open, then our pawn structure compared to White is not that sound. }
14... c6
{ 14...d5 =  Once again, this was certainly possible and looks more to the point. }
15. Bd3 Be6 { Perhaps next on the agenda is the ...d5 break. } 16. Rf2 Qb6
{ Slowly but surely, Black is taking over as his pieces are crashing through by attacking White's vulnerable pawns. }
17. Nf1 Rf7
{ Feels a bit slow as White can now bring all his pieces to the party.   17...d5 =  Once more, I would prefer this move over the text move which resolves the centre quickly and opens up the game. }
18. Qh5
{ With this Queen move, White still cannot bring his f1-Knight to play as it is tied down to defend the e3-pawn from our Queen on b6. So, it is just a waste of time to advance the Queen further without paying heed to the f1-Knight.   18.Qd2 !  Overprotecting the pawn on e3 and now the Knight on f1 will land on g3 creating ruckus on our backward pawn on f6.  18...d5  Now it is too late as White's pieces are well armed and will be met by  19.Ng3  +=  And White is better as the other Rook on a1 is coming to f1 to exert pressure on the f6-pawn. }
18... Rg8
{ All of Black's pieces are well coordinated. The only hindrance is the pawn structure. }
19. Re1
{ So Vishy protects the e3-pawn so that he can bring his Knight but the drawback is that the a2-pawn is hanging. }
19... d5
{ Finally, the d5-break has seen its light.   19...Bxa2  was definitely possible and White has to prove his compensation. But perhaps in the game, Ivanchuk was worried about drifting the Bishop too far away from the kingside as White can lock the Bishop temporarily by  20.c4  Bb3  21.Ng3  d5 !  Black is in time to create counterplay, but was not an easy decision over the board. }
20. Ng3
{ I believe that this is where Anand starts to go astray. The position is still balanced, but Black is now the one who is dictating the game. }
20... d4 { The tables are turning :@@EndBracket@@. } 21. exd4 exd4 22. e5
{ Anand was hoping for an active defense with the text move, but it backfires as he loses a pawn and the pin on f2 will become a deadly weapon in Black's hand.   22.cxd4  was necessary to save the position from drowning.  22...Qxd4  23.Be2  Ne5  Albeit, practically Black has good chances to create some play here with a powerful Knight on e5. }
22... dxc3 23. Bxg6 Rxg6 24. bxc3 Bg4
{ Pushing the Queen back to an inferior square. } 25. Qh4 fxe5
{ Black is clearly a pawn up and also the Rook on f2 is tied down, thanks to the pin along the b6-g1 diagonal. }
26. Ne4 Be6 27. Kh1 { Moving away from the pin. } 27... Rxf2 28. Nxf2 Qb2
{ The Queen is piercing through White's camp. } 29. Rd1 Qe2
{ 29...Qxa2  ∓  Grabbing one more pawn and Black is on top. At times, we have to be greedy :@@EndBracket@@. }
30. h3 h6
{ This just makes things a bit shaky. Instead, Ivanchuk could place his bishop on the excellent post of d5. This multi-purpose move closes the d-file and attacks the g2 point at the same time. I can assume that this was the time trouble phase in the game. So both the sides made some back to back errors.   30...Bd5 !  31.Qd8+  Kg7  32.Qe7+  Bf7  33.Qh4  h5  ∓  followed by ...Bd5 and this time it is deadly because the Black king will be sheltered on the h-file @@StartBracket@@ h6 square @@EndBracket@@. }
31. Kh2 Qe3 32. Rd8+ Kh7 33. Rb8
{ The Rook move to b8 is a waste of time.   33.a4  or   33.Re8  was necessary to keep the game going. }
33... Rg7 { Once again, Black is regaining his lost advantage. } 34. Rf8 Qg5
{ On a closer glimpse, Black is a pawn up so his decision to exchange queens makes much sense. Especially in time trouble, it is a great decision to get rid of the attacking piece when you have more material. }
35. Qe4+ Qg6 36. g4 Bxa2
{ 36...Qxe4  Clearly the best move as the option in the game allowed some counterplay for White.  37.Nxe4  Bxa2  -+  And Black is winning. }
37. Qxe5 Qe6 38. Qf4 Rf7
{ All of White's active pieces are getting exchanged. With more pawns, it's a matter of time to convert it to a winning position. }
39. Rxf7+ Qxf7 40. Qe4+ Kg7
{ 40...Kg8  ∓  Some precision is needed as the King is clearly safer on the light squares than on the dark squares. }
41. Nd3 Qc7+ 42. Ne5 Qd6 43. Kg3 a5 { The corner pawn has to be pushed! } 44.
Qf4 a4 45. g5 hxg5 46. Qxg5+ Kf8 47. c4 c5 48. Qf5+ Ke7 49. Kg2 Bb3
{ 49...Qe6  -+  has to be played in order to escape with our King from checks. }
50. Qe4
{ 50.Qh7+ =  is already a draw as White's Queen will keep harassing the Black King with checks. }
50... b6
{ 50...a3  would have sealed White's fate much earlier.  51.Qxb7+  Ke6  52.Qxb3  Qd2+  53.Kf3  a2 !!  And Black wins!  54.Nd3  Kf5  -+  Precision to the core as if   54...a1=Q  it would lead to perpetual to  55.Qb6  So with the King move, we are threatening to Queen next. White cannot move his Queen at the same time, as the d3-Knight has to be protected. }
51. Ng4+ Qe6 52. Qb7+ Kf8 53. Qb8+ Kg7 54. Qc7+ Kg6 55. Qf4 Bc2 56. Qh6+ Kf7
57. Qf4+ Kg7 58. Qc1 Be4+ 59. Kg3 Qd6+ 60. Kh4 Qe7+ 61. Kg3 Qd6+ 62. Kh4 Kf7
63. Qb2 Bf5 64. Qf2 Kg6 65. Qa2 Bxg4 66. hxg4 Qd8+ 67. Kg3 Qd3+ 68. Kh4 a3 69.
Qa1 Kf7
{ And Finally after a series of moves, Black has won the battle. A nice game by Ivanchuk. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Adams, Michael vs. Radjabov, Teimour, (Rogaska Slatina 2011)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now we will see the game of Jaenisch expert Teimour Radjabov, The Azeri King. This will be of great interest to see how Radjabov deals with this opening and outplayed the positional maestro Adams. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Teimour, a brilliant player and now a hilarious Youtube streamer. Do check out his channel if you have want to have some fun, and of course to learn some chess! He was exclusively playing the Jaenisch back in the mid-2000s. }
4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5
{ Teimour always preferred to place his bishop on c5, rather than the other idea with 6...d6 and ...Be7. }
7. Qd3
{ This is one of the critical options apart from   7.Nc3  which was played in the previous game of Anand-Ivanchuk 2011. The Queen on d3 simply protects the e4-pawn and keeps control over the vulnerable light squares. It also comes with the sneaky idea of Qc4+ winning a piece on c5, if Black castles. }
7... Nd4
{ gives White some play compared to the recommended move 7...d6 in the opening chapter. We will see in this game at some point White could have gained the upper hand. But I would like to show this game to understand the middle game nuances and not from the opening point of view.   7...d6  is the main critical line which was recommended by me and is dealt in theopening section. Lets stick to the game here. }
8. Nxd4
{ 8.Nxe5  White can grab the central pawn, but in turn he also loses the e4-pawn back after...  8...Qe7  9.Nf3  Nxb5  10.Qxb5  Nxe4  and Black is doing fine in the resulting complications. }
8... Bxd4 9. Bc4 { Prevents O-O. } 9... Qe7
{ The idea is to play ...d6 followed by ...Be6 in order to castle. } 10. a4
{ With a sneaky threat of c3 and then a5, trapping our dark-squared Bishop. }
10... a6 { So that our Bishop can hide on a7. } 11. Nc3 d6 12. Bg5
{ Preparing Nd5. } 12... c6
{ Prevents Nd5, but White can reroute the Knight on c3 to g3 eyeing the f5-square. }
13. Ne2 Bc5 14. c3
{ 14.Ng3  Continuing the plan and White's Knight on g3 keeps an eye on the f5-square to hassle the Queen on e7.  14...h6  15.Be3  Bxe3  16.Qxe3  Be6  17.Rad1 !!  A brilliant computer-ish move with the point that   17...Bc4  fails to  18.Nf5  and the d6-pawn falls apart.  17...O-O-O  17...O-O  is also not possible because of   18.Nf5  and Black's position is collapsing.  18.Bxe6+  Qxe6  19.b4  ±  And Black's position looks really dangerous with the White pawns marching ahead to weaken the King. }
14... h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. b4 Bb6 17. Kh1 { Preparing f4, so what to do? }
17... g5
{ Of course, this is the way :@@EndBracket@@, Prophylaxis. The standard idea to prevent the break of White with f4. We will see this idea of ...g5 quite often in the other games as well. }
18. f3 h5 19. b5
{ Trying to break open the position as our king is in the center. } 19... axb5
20. axb5 Rxa1 21. Rxa1 Kd8
{ Bringing the king to c7 where it simply protects everything. } 22. bxc6 bxc6
23. Rf1 Kc7
{ Suddenly after some passive moves by White, Black has in fact gained the upper hand. Now the two Bishops will begin to speak and dance :@@EndBracket@@. }
24. Nc1 Rf8 25. Qd1 Qg6 26. Be2 g4 { Black is gradually outplaying White. } 27.
Nd3 gxf3 28. Rxf3 Rxf3 29. Bxf3 { The e4-pawn stands lonely now. } 29... h4 30.
Nb4 Qg5 31. Qe1 Be6 { All pieces are coming into play. } 32. Nd3 Bc4 33. Nf2 d5
{ Now it is the time to advance further. } 34. Nh3 Qe3 35. Qxe3 Bxe3
{ The king is in prison controlled by the two bishops. } 36. g3 hxg3 37. hxg3
Bd2 38. Kg2 Bxc3 39. g4 d4 40. g5 Bd2 41. g6 Be3 42. Kg3 c5 43. Kh4 Bg8 44. Ng5
c4 45. Nf7 Bf4 46. Be2 d3 47. Bf1 Kd7 48. Kh5 Ke7 49. Nh6 Bxh6 50. Kxh6 Kf6 51.
g7 Kf7 52. Kg5 Kxg7 53. Kf5 d2 54. Be2 c3 55. Bd1 Bc4 56. Kxe5 Bd3
{ A fantastic win by Radjabov outclassing Adams. This game showcased the power of the bishop pair and prominent ideas like ...g5 for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Adhiban, Baskaran vs. Nezad, Husein Aziz, (Ho Chi Minh City 2012)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. Nc3
{ In the previous games we checked the positional approach with 4. d3. Now comes, the old mainline with 4.Nc3. }
4... fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Qe2
{ is the critical option and as well discussed exclusively in the openings section. }
7... Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe5 Qe6
{ The idea is that White cannot castle immediately because of the pin as after ...d6, he loses the piece.   9...Bb7  is the new move discussed in theopening chapters. The text move with 9...Qe6 was heavily played those days. }
10. Ng4
{ Adhiban wants to place his Knight on e3 after the exchange of queens.   10.d4  is the main move, which is probed in the forthcoming correspondence game later in this chapter. }
10... Qxe2+
{ 10...d6  Perhaps was more precise, maintaining the tension.  11.Qxe6  Bxe6  12.Ne3  Bf6  The two bishops are radiant and create a lot of pressure on White's pawns. The c1-Bishop now finds it difficult to come into play as it is tied down to defend the b2-pawn. So, White clearly lacks development to make use of his extra pawn.  13.d3  Kd7 =  with good compensation. }
11. Kxe2 O-O 12. Rf1
{ Looks a bit weird as White is supposed to develop his pieces rather than making passive moves. }
12... d5
{ Already it is looking dangerous for White as now his knight will be disturbed by our central pawn. }
13. Ne5
{ 13.Ne3  Bd6 !  Also now we see why the Rook on f1 is pointless. The h2-pawn is attacked.  14.d3  Bd7  =+  Immediate   14...Bxh2  will be met by  15.g3  so Black improves his position and plans to bring the a8-Rook to e8 before taking on the challenge by capturing on h2. }
13... Bd6 14. f4
{ Perhaps this was the idea of Adhiban behind playing Rf1 so that he can support the Knight on e5 by f4. But Black has a nice resource here, destroying the defender by... }
14... g5 15. Rf2
{ 15.d3  gxf4  16.Bxf4  Rxf4 !  is the trick.  17.Rxf4  Bxe5  -+ } 15... gxf4
{ 15...c5  =+  is a brilliant prophylactic move preventing White's consolidation with d4. The f4-pawn is anyway ours. So next on the agenda is 16...gxf4 and Black is on top. }
16. d4
{ White sort of consolidates now but Black is still in the drivers seat, thanks to the bishop pair. }
16... Ba6+ 17. Kf3
{ Too bold to march ahead as our Bishops are damn scary.   17.Kd1 =  was necessary to safeguard the King. }
17... Rae8 18. Bxf4 c5
{ Deflecting the pawn on d4 which is supporting the e5-Knight. } 19. c3
{ 19.g3  Only move to save the position from drowning.  19...cxd4  20.Nd3  And White is in time to hold. }
19... cxd4 20. cxd4 c5
{ And now it is deadly as White can no longer hold on to the d4-pawn. Also, he can no longer bring the Knight to d3, like in the 19.g3 variation as it is now unprotected there. }
21. Re1 cxd4 { White is simply busted here. } 22. Kg3 d3 23. h3 Bxe5 24. Bxe5
Rxf2 25. Kxf2 d2 26. Rd1 Rxe5 27. Rxd2 Kf7 28. Kf3 Kf6 29. g4 Bb7 30. Kf2 Re4
31. Rd3 d4 32. Ra3 a6 33. Rb3 Bd5
{ A nice game by Nezad showcasing the superiority of the bishop pair. Often we tend to get such positions, where we have the bishop pair while White has an extra pawn. In most cases, we have more than enough compensation. This game is one more example of it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kasimdzhanov, Rustam vs. Nyback, Tomi, (Khanty-Mansiysk 2010)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between the former World Champion Rustam Kasimdzhanov and the Finland's No.1 Tomi Nyback. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ Apart from   6...Bc5  I have also suggested an alternative for Black with 6..d6 with the intent to develop the Bishop to e7, in the opening section too. So both the alternatives are equally interesting. }
7. Qd3
{ The point is of course to protect the e4-pawn and also it refrains the Queen from the pin with ...Bg4.   7.Bc4 !  is an acid test which puts Black under pressure. Hop on to theopening section to know more details on this move :@@EndBracket@@. Lets continue with the move played in the game. }
7... a6
{ The drawback of the Queen on d3 is that it blocks the Bishop on b5. We can attack it immediately to gain two bishops and White is forced to concede the Bishop as it has no room to go back. }
8. Bxc6+
{ 8.Bc4  Na5  And thats the end of story for the Bishop on c4.  9.Nc3  Nxc4  10.Qxc4  Qd7 =  We will interpose next with...Qf7 and all is good. }
8... bxc6 9. Nc3 h6
{ Black's idea is to prepare ...g5 followed by... Bg7 as the central pawns on d6 and e5 are formidable. Moreover, the ...g5 idea simply prevents White from playing f4 and our centre will become even stronger and sturdier. }
10. Rd1 { The Threat is Ne5. } 10... Bd7 { 10...Be6 is also equally good. } 11.
Nd2 g5 { Continuing the Plan. } 12. Nc4 Bg7 13. Na5 Qe7
{ The point is that whenever White plays Qc4, we can meet it with ...Qf7 and exchange the Queens. This will only benefit us with the bishop pair in hand. }
14. Qc4 Qf7 15. Qxf7+ Kxf7
{ Black is clearly better here as he has the bishop pair, formidable centre, and well coordinated pieces. }
16. b4 Rhf8 17. Bd2 Kg6 18. Re1 Rf7 { 18...g4  =+  is also better for Black. }
19. Rad1 Raf8 20. Bc1 Nh5 { The Knight is heading to f4. } 21. Be3 Nf4 22. Nb1
h5 { Pushing the pawns forward to start an attack. } 23. c4 h4 24. h3 g4 25.
hxg4 Bxg4
{ Our pieces are simply in commanding positions and White is on the verge of collapsing. }
26. f3 Nxg2 { Bam!... A nice tactical blow. } 27. fxg4
{ 27.Kxg2  Bxf3+  28.Kh2  Bxd1  29.Rxd1  Rf1  30.Nc3  Rxd1  31.Nxd1  Rf1  -+  And the Black Rook simply destroys White's position by attacking all the pawns. }
27... Nxe1 28. Rxe1 Bh6
{ The Bishop on g7 was blocked by his own pawns on e5 and d6 and hence by...Bh6, we exchange the important piece on e3 so that our Rook can enter the seventh rank now. }
29. Nd2 Bxe3+ 30. Rxe3 Rf2
{ The Rook is heavenly on the second rank for Black. } 31. Rd3 Kg5
{ The King is a useful piece in the endgame. Use it! } 32. c5 h3
{ And Black is winning hands down. } 33. Nac4 Rg2+ 34. Kh1 Rff2 35. Rxh3 Rxd2
36. Nxd2 Rxd2 37. Ra3 d5
{ We have an active king and our pawns are simply rolling where White's king is stuck on the first rank. }
38. Kg1 Kxg4 39. Rxa6 Kf3 40. Rxc6 dxe4 41. Rf6+ Ke2 42. b5 e3 43. b6 cxb6 44.
cxb6 Rxa2 45. b7 Rb2 46. Rf7 Kd1 47. Re7 e2 48. Rd7+ Ke1 49. Kg2 e4 50. Kg1 Rb5
51. Kg2 Rb6 52. Kg1 Rg6+ 53. Kh2 Rg8 54. Rc7 Rb8
{ A fascinating game by Nyback who simply outplayed Kasimdzhanov. Once again, we can witness how powerful the bishops are. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Dunlop, Gordon vs. Williamson, Harvey D, (ICCF email 2016)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This model game is a correspondence game between two strong players. } 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Qe2 Be7 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe5 Qe6
{ The idea is ...d6.   9...Bb7  A rare and unexplored option is my recommendation.  9...Qe6 is heavily played but I found 9...Bb7 more to the spirit of the position as we are planning for long castle and to open up the position with ...c5. Yes, you can probe theopening section to more know about it. Now lets see 9...Qe6. }
10. d4
{ 10.Ng4  played in the game of Adhiban-Nezad, was too slow and already analysed in the third game of this chapter. }
10... Bf6 { Logical move to exert pressure on the f6-a1 diagonal. } 11. c3
{ 11.Nf3  Qxe2+  12.Kxe2  Ba6+  13.Kd1  d6  =∞  And as always we have good compensation in the form of the bishop pair. }
11... c5 { Breaking the centre. } 12. Ng4 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 Bh4
{ Maintaining the two bishops. The bishop on h4 looks weird, but it has its key points. There is pressure on the f2-pawn now and White cannot kick our Bishop by g3 as it will only weaken his light squares. }
14. Re1
{ 14.dxc5  d6  15.Ne3  Ba6+  16.c4   16.Ke1  dxc5  and White's king is stuck in the centre.  16...d5 !  And thanks to the pin, Black maintains good play for the pawn.  17.Rd1  O-O-O  =∞ }
14... O-O
{ The threat is now ...d6 to attack the g4-Knight which is defending the f2-pawn. So, now White is forced to kick our bishop which in turn weakens his light squares. }
15. g3 Ba6+ 16. Kd1 Bd8 { The bishop always has maximum range. } 17. Be3
{ Supporting the f2-pawn.   17.dxc5?  loses to  17...h5!  And when the White Knight moves, we capture on f2. }
17... cxd4 18. Bxd4
{ 18.cxd4  is also possible.  18...d6  Threatening ...Bc8 to corner the g4-Knight.  19.f4  So that now the Knight can jump to f2 where it is more safe.  19...Bc8  20.Nf2  a5  =∞  And Black has enough compensation for the pawn as the light squares are clearly vulnerable. }
18... d6 19. f4 Bc8 20. Nf2 c5 21. Be3 a5
{ The corner pawn push is always useful in these kind of endgames. The idea is simply that we gain space and can also be used to break White's pawn structure with ...a4-a3 in the future. }
22. b3 a4 23. b4 cxb4 24. cxb4 Bf6 25. Rc1 Be6
{ Once again the two bishops dominate. } 26. Ne4 Bb2 27. Rc7 Rfc8
{ First exchanging the active piece of White, in order to get rid of any active play of the rook. }
28. Bb6 Bxa2 { Now the a4-pawn is pretty dangerous for White to deal with. }
29. Kc2 a3 30. Nxd6 Rxc7+ 31. Bxc7 g6 { Providing some space for the king. }
32. Rd1 Ra4 33. Ba5 Bg7 34. Ne4 Be6
{ Next on the agenda is ...a2 as we have removed the bishops. } 35. Nc5 Bg4
{ is a nice little intermezzo. } 36. Rc1
{ 36.Rd8+  Kf7  37.Nxa4  a2  -+  And White is simply unable to prevent us from making a queen. }
36... a2 { With a nice tactical idea in mind! } 37. Nxa4 Bf5+ 38. Kb3 Bb1
{ The point and the pawn on a2 is now promoting to a queen which is unstoppable. }
39. Rc8+ Kf7 40. Rc7+ Ke6 41. Nc5+ Kf5 42. Rxg7 a1=Q 43. Rxh7 Ba2+ 44. Kc2 Qb1+
45. Kc3 Qe1+ 46. Kc2 Kg4 47. Rd7 Qb1+ 48. Kc3 Qc1+ 49. Kd3 Kh3 50. Rh7+ Kg2
{ And apparently Black won this game. A beautiful demonstration of the bishop pair once again. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Guseinov, Gadir vs. Oleksiyenko, Mykhailo, (Abu Dhabi 2013)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5 7. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Black gives the pawn in order to obtain the bishop pair and get an active position. After all, it's a gambit line :@@EndBracket@@! }
8. Nxe5 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We will see   9.Nc3  in the next game which is the mainline. Apart from that, the text move is also critical. }
9... Qe8 10. Bxf6
{ White exchanges the Knight on f6 so that there is no more pressure on the e4-pawn. The drawback is of course White has to be careful about Black's radiant and dangerous Bishops. }
10... Rxf6 11. Nd3
{ Only move as if   11.Nf3  then  11...Ba6  12.Re1  Qh5  followed by Raf8. This looks extremely dangerous for White as all of Black's pieces are penetrating into the kingside. }
11... Bd4
{ This typical move provoking c3 which takes away the square for the b1-Knight is seen in many cases in the opening section. }
12. c3
{ 12.Nd2  is also possible and is dealt extensively in the opening section. }
12... Bb6 13. e5
{ White releases the tension and attacks the Rook. If   13.Nd2  then  13...d5  was the novelty recommended by me in the opening chapter. For more details about this move, you can always switch back to the opening section. }
13... Rf8 14. Nd2 d5 { Opening up the position. } 15. exd6 Ba6
{ Oleksiyenko goes for quick development instead of grabbing the pawn which is also possible but 15...cxd6 is simpler.   15...cxd6  is the prescribed move in the opening chapter  16.Nc4  Bc7 =  And Black has great compensation for the pawn, thanks to the Bishop pair once again. }
16. c4
{ 16.Qb3+  was necessary and leads to complexity after  16...Kh8  17.Rae1   17.c4  And the difference between 16. c4 and now on 17th move is that the Queen is activated. In the game with 16.c4, it was not easy to get the Queen out.  17...cxd6  18.Rae1  Qg6  19.Qc3  Bc8  Re-routing the Bishop as on a6 it was blocked by the c4-pawn and moreover, the ...d5 break was not effective in this particular position.  If   19...d5  then White can respond with  20.Ne5  or   20.b3  17...Qg6  18.Ne5  Qf5  The bishop pair and the battery on the f-file is extremely scary for White.  19.c4  Only move to save the f1-Rook.  19...Bxf2+  20.Kh1  20...cxd6  21.Re2  Qh5 !   21...dxe5  22.Rexf2  Qxf2  23.Rxf2  Rxf2  24.Qe3  and it is a complex position where White is slightly better as the Bishop on a6 is shut down.  22.Rexf2  Rxf2  23.Rxf2  Qxe5  And all the forthcoming moves are pretty forced which fizzles out to a draw after  24.Qf3  Setting up a sneaky trap of Qf8 mate.  24...Rg8 !  25.Qxc6  Qe1+  26.Rf1  Qxd2  27.Qxa6  Qxb2  28.Qxd6  Qxa2  29.c5  Qc4 =  And Black controls the passed pawn on c5 with an equal game. }
16... cxd6
{ Next on the agenda is...Qg6, attacking the d3-Knight which is holding on to the f2 pawn. Also, ...d5 is floating in the air, sometimes to open up the a6-Bishop. }
17. Qg4
{ White plans to activate the Queen on the kingside preventing ...Qg6, but is harassed by...   17.Qa4  Qg6 !  is the point counterattacking the Knight on d3  18.Qxa6  Qxd3  19.Nf3  Rf4  Attacking the c4-pawn and also planning to double on the f-file with ...Raf8. This creates a huge amount of pressure on the f3-Knight and the f2-pawn.  20.Rad1  20.Rac1 Raf8 is the idea.  20...Qxc4  21.Qxc4+  Rxc4  22.Rxd6  Rc2  The Rook on the seventh rank is always annoying and Black obtains good compensation for the pawn.  23.Rd2  Rxd2  24.Nxd2  Re8 !  Once again, the Rook is eyeing to come to e2-square.  25.Nc4  Re2  Rook on seven is heaven and White's Rook on f1 is tied down to defend the f2-pawn. If he exchanges the b6-Bishop, this would lead to a Rook endgame after  26.Nxb6  axb6  27.Rb1  b5 =  The active Rook on e2 compensates for the pawn. An equal game. }
17... h5 18. Qd1
{ Not a good sign for White as he has wasted a move with his Queen   18.Qg3  Qe2  And Black is piercing through White's camp.  19.Rad1  h4  Deflecting the Queen which is supporting the d3-Knight.  20.Qg6  Rae8  ∓  Dream scenario for Black where all of their pieces are working and White is collapsing here. }
18... d5 { 18...Qg6  is also good. } 19. Qc2 Qg6
{ White is getting slowly outplayed. } 20. Qc3 Rad8 21. Nb4
{ White goes astray as he is unable to bear the tension as now the Knight on b4 is far away from the kingside.   21.Ne5  Qf6  22.Ndf3  g5  =+  And the pawns are rolling to disturb the Knights. }
21... Bc8 22. c5
{ Now we see that White wanted to play c5 with his move Nb4 so as to reduce the pressure on the c4-pawn. Now, the Bishop on c7 and c8 becomes a deadly combination in attacking the White King. }
22... Bc7 23. Nb3 a5 24. Nd3 d4
{ Not giving the Knight on b3 to occupy the d4-square and seal the position. }
25. Qd2 { 25.Nxd4  Qe4  wins the piece. } 25... Bh3 26. f3 Bxg2 27. Qxg2 Qxd3
28. Nd2 Rd5 { Bringing the Rook into play. Black is clearly winning here. } 29.
Ne4 Rdf5 30. Rad1 Qe3+ 31. Kh1 Be5
{ Many alternatives win here and 31...Be5 is one of them. } 32. Nd2 d3 33. Nc4
Qd4 34. Nxe5 Rxe5 35. Qg6 d2 36. Qxc6 Rxc5 37. Qe6+ Kh8 38. Qe7 Rcf5 39. Qe2
Rd8 { The d2-pawn is deadly. } 40. b3 Re5 41. Qg2 Qc3 42. Qg3 Re2 43. Qg5 Rd6
44. h3 Rf6 45. Qxh5+ Rh6 46. Qg4 Qc7 47. f4 Qc6+
{ And Black snatched away the victory. What a beautiful game demonstrating the power of the bishop pair once again! If White doesn't know what he is doing, he can easily end up like this game. The compensation for the pawn is so powerful and energetic. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bok, Benjamin vs. Pruijssers, Roeland, (Stroebeck 2013) "]
[Result "*"]

{ Now we come to the final game in the model games chapter .This game is between two strong Dutch players, Bok and Pruijssers. I should also mention that GM Pruijssers along with Radjabov made tremendous effort to popularize the Jaenisch Gambit and has played a important role scoring many wins in this line. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8.
Nxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 { The main line. In the previous game we dealt with   9.Bg5 }
9... d6 10. Na4
{ 10.Nd3  is also one of the options. For more details about this move, you can check the opening section. }
10... Qe8 11. Nd3 Bg4 { Forcing the Queen to move to an inferior square. } 12.
Qe1 Bd4 { Provoking c3 is the standard idea in these types of opening lines. }
13. c3 Bb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. f3 Be6
{ is the critical position which remains an acid test for Black. Black is a pawn down and he has also lost the Bishop pair. But, thanks to the opposite-colored Bishops on the board, he has good chances to hold the position and obtain good compensation. And in fact in this game, Black even won. }
16. a3 Bc4 17. Qd1 Qf7 18. Re1 Rae8
{ 18...Bb3  is a strong novelty which was prescribed in the opening section.  In this game,18...Rae8 was played, which looked natural. }
19. Bg5
{ 19.Be3  d5  Black opens up the game and tries to exchange some pawns in order to neutralize but after  20.e5  Nd7  21.Bf2 !  Bxd3  22.e6 !  The key intermezzo!  22...Rxe6  23.Rxe6  Qxe6  24.Qxd3  +=  may give White a microscopic edge because of the doubled pawns. }
19... Nd7 20. Be3 Re6 { Bringing the Rook to the kingside. } 21. Kh1 Rf6
{ Albeit White has an extra pawn and Black has no real counterplay, it is not easy for White to make progress. }
22. Nf2 Bb3 23. Qe2 Bc4 24. Qd1 Bb3 25. Qe2 c5
{ It is interesting to note that Black rejects the repetition and aims for a pawn down position. It just shows that White has no constructive plans with the extra pawn. Although, there was no reason to play for more but perhaps the tournament situation demanded and hence Pruijssers wanted to win at all cost. }
26. f4
{ Not a fan of this move as the center is not intact, like in the case of the formation with f3-e4. }
26... d5 { Black seizes the opportunity now to challenge the e4-pawn. } 27. e5
Rg6 { Now the light squares are in Black's control. } 28. Bd2
{ Threatening e6. } 28... Re6
{ One of the ideas is Nb8-c6-e7-f5 :@@EndBracket@@. } 29. Nh3 h6 30. Ng1
{ White also wants to maneuver his Knight to f3, but is a mistake now as White forgot about }
30... Nf6
{ Now the tables have turned as our Knight will occupy the key e4-square from where it is unrivalled. }
31. Be3 Ne4 32. Nf3 { The idea is to challenge the active Knight on e4. } 32...
Bc4 33. Qd1 Rd8
{ is too slow and hands over the advantage to White.   33...Qxf4 !!  is a cool tactic which Black missed during the game.  34.Bxf4  Nf2+  35.Kg1  Nxd1  36.Raxd1   36.Bc1  Bb3  is there.  36...Rxf4  =+  And Black has regained the pawn with a better position. }
34. a4 Ree8 35. Qc2 Qh5 36. b3
{ 36.a5  is more precise and then b3 next. In the game, Black was able to bring his Bishop to c8. }
36... Ba6 37. a5 Bc8 38. axb6
{ A terrible mistake as it kills most of White's chances.   38.a6 !  The passed pawn has to be pushed and White is clearly better here. }
38... cxb6 39. Kg1 Bf5 { And the tables have turned again to Black's favor. }
40. Qc1 Re6 41. Ra2 Rg6 { White is doomed to passivity. } 42. Rf1 Bg4 43. f5
Bxf5 44. Nh4 Qxh4 45. Rxf5 Re6 46. Ra7 Qg4 47. Qf1 Rg6
{ 47...Nxc3??  would be blunder because of  48.Rg5  followed by Qf7-Qg7 mate. }
48. Rf4 Qe6 49. c4 Ng5 50. Rf5 Nh3+ 51. Kh1 dxc4 52. Ra1 cxb3
{ The pawns roll now. } 53. gxh3 b2 54. Rb1 c4 55. Rf4
{ 55.Rxb2  Qxf5  56.Qxf5  Rd1  is mate. } 55... Qc6+ 56. Qf3 Rd3
{ Gives some counterplay for White.   56...c3  -+  is simple and White is forced to resign here. }
57. Qxc6 Rxc6 58. Bd4 Rxd4 { 58...c3  59.Bxc3  is a draw. } 59. Rxd4 c3 60. Rb4
{ Black has clearly messed up big time and now White has survived. } 60... Kf7
{ 60...c2  61.R4xb2  and White is in time to neutralize. } 61. Kg2
{ A favor in return   61.Re1  Ke6  and  62.Rb5  c2  63.Rxb2  is a draw. } 61...
Ke6 { The point is that the e5-pawn is attacked and if White protects it with }
62. Re1 Kd5
{ is the difference. If White had played Re1 before 61.Kg2, he would have time to cut the King by Rb5 and here he is not in time. A subtle but yet a game changing difference and White is busted now. }
63. Kf3 Kc5 64. Rxb2 cxb2 65. Rb1 Kd4 66. Rxb2 Kxe5 67. Ke3 Rc3+ 68. Kf2 Rc6
69. Ke3 Kd5 70. Rd2+ Kc5 71. Rd7 Re6+ 72. Kf4 g6 73. Rc7+ Kd5 74. Rd7+ Kc6 75.
Rd1 b5 76. Rc1+ Kb6 77. Rb1 Re2 78. Rg1 g5+ 79. Kg3 Re3+ 80. Kg4 Re4+ 81. Kg3
Rf4 82. Re1 Kc5 83. Re5+ Kc4 84. Re6 Rh4 85. Rc6+ Kb3
{ And finally Black won this roller-coaster of a game. Hope you guys enjoyed all of the beautiful games. Hail the Jaenisch Gambit! It always provides complex fights even in endgames like this one. }
*

