[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr3/ppp3kp/2pb4/5p2/8/2pQ1N2/PPP2PPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black seems to be in some trouble with his wide open king. With which move can he keep the balance? }
12... f4
{ Shutting the c1-Bishop out of play and Black is totally fine here. Next, we will bring our Queen to f6 followed by ...Bf5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/8/5N2/PPPPQPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How to develop our pieces quickly? Find the best move. } 6... Bd6
{ An unusual development as it blocks the d-pawn but the point is clearly seen: to protect the e5-pawn and aim for a quick castle. }
7. O-O
{ 7.d4  White tries to act immediately in the center, but without proper development it backfires.  7...e4  8.Ng5  If   8.c3  a6  9.Ba4  then we comeback with our Bishop to e7 and White has issues with his f3-Knight.  8...Qe7  The pawn on d4 is hanging now. }
7... O-O 8. Nc3
{ 8.Bxc6  dxc6  9.Nxe5  Re8  10.d4  c5  and White faces issues with his e5-Knight. }
8... a6 9. Bxc6
{ White gives up the Bishop to capture the e5-pawn but after... } 9... dxc6 10.
Nxe5 Re8 { He is unable to defend, holding on to his extra pawn as after.. }
11. f4 Ng4 12. d4 c5
{ Attacking anything which comes in between to support the e5-Knight. } 13. h3
cxd4 14. Qc4+ { 14.hxg4  dxc3  is there. } 14... Be6 15. Qxd4 Bxe5
{ And the position is fizzled out. } 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. fxe5 Nxe5
{ Finally the dust has settled and Black has a comfortable equality here as the pawn structure is symmetrical with no weaknesses on both sides. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pp1p2pp/8/1p2P3/4N3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black is a piece up but his position is cramped. How do we free the position and bring our pieces into play? }
8... d5
{ is the freeing move which solves the problem of our King immediately and we end up with easy development for our pieces. }
9. exd6 Nf6 10. Bg5
{ 10.O-O  Nxe4  11.Qh5+  g6  12.Qe5  Kf7  13.Qxh8  and  13...Nf6  locking in the Queen  14.Bh6  Be6  and the two pieces are far superior to the Rook here. }
10... Qa5+ { Moving out of the pin. } 11. Nc3
{ 11.Bd2  b4  is also winning for Black. } 11... b4 12. Bxf6
{ Find a brilliant intermezzo which increases the advantage and kills all the counterplay for White. }
12... Qf5
{ The point is that if we take on f6 with   12...gxf6  then White can shut our Queen out on a5 by  13.Nd5  and create counterplay around our King. This intermezzo just kills the idea and brings the Queen to defend the King. Moreover, the two pieces are still under attack so we maintain an extra piece at the end of the story :@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Bh4 bxc3 14. O-O Kf7
{ And our King is safe and secured on f7. White clearly has no enough compensation for the piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bk3r/p1p1b2p/2P2np1/8/7q/3P2N1/PPP2QPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black would like to play ...Ng4 - how can he make it work? } 16... Bd7
{ The immediate   16...Ng4  fails to  17.Qd4  and the Rook is hanging on h8. The text move blocks the d-file from checks. }
17. cxd7 Ng4
{ There is no check on d4 which is blocked by the d7-pawn. White cannot save both the Queen and the pawn on h2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp3pp/2N2n2/1B6/4p3/3P4/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is threatening a discovered check. How should Black respond to this? }
8... Qd6 { The key move. There is no proper discovered check for White. } 9.
Nxa7+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Be3 b6 { and the Knight is in graveyard. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp4p/2n2p2/1B1pp3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the move which holds the center together! } 8... Qd6
{ Holding on to the center and also getting the pieces out quickly for long castle. }
9. O-O Bg4 { What else apart from pinning :@@EndBracket@@. } 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4
{ Daring play from White to get rid of the pin. } 11... Bg6 12. dxe5 fxe5 13.
c4
{ The center has to be broken, otherwise g4 advance will be a clear target. }
13... O-O-O 14. Qxd5 Qxd5 15. cxd5 Rxd5 16. Bc4 Rd6
{ An important retreat to prevent Be6+ otherwise Black is simply worse. Next, Black is planning to play ...h5, maintaining the balance. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp3pp/2n2n2/1B2N3/2Q1p3/8/PPPP1PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How to cope up with the mate on f7? } 8... Qd6
{ Attacking the active Knight on e5 which creates a lot of play around our King. }
9. Nf7 Qe6
{ We will lose the Rook now but the h8-Knight is sealed once the knight takes it. We already have an extra piece, so most likely we will have two pieces for the Rook. }
10. Nxh8 a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qc3
{ Dimov,I @@StartBracket@@2457@@EndBracket@@-Rebord,M @@StartBracket@@2531@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2007. }
12... Nd5
{ improvement over the correspondence game, as this move harasses the Queen and we are better after... }
13. Qg3 Qf6 { With ...Bd6 to follow and the position is collapsing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/ppp4p/2n2p2/1B1pp2b/6P1/5N1P/PPPPQP2/R1B2RK1 b kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How do we continue the attack? Find a breathtaking move here. } 10... Bd6
{ A brilliant move sacrificing the piece. } 11. d4
{ 11.gxh5  White takes up the challenge and takes the piece but the resulting complications end in a draw after...  11...Rg8+  12.Kh1  White cannot place the King on h2 because of the Bishop on d6.  12...Qd7  13.Ng1  Only move to protect the h3-pawn.  13...O-O-O  14.f4  Rxg1+ !  The much expected shot to destroy the defender.  15.Rxg1  Qxh3+  16.Qh2  Qf3+  17.Qg2  Qxh5+ =  And a repetition. White is unable to avoid the draw. }
11... e4 12. Bxc6+
{ 12.gxh5  Qd7  coming for the h3-pawn and  13.Bxc6  bxc6  will transpose to the mainline. }
12... bxc6 13. gxh5 Qd7 14. Nh2 Qxh3 15. f4 { Renewing communications. } 15...
Kf7 { Adding more fire to the position by bringing the a8-Rook into action. }
16. Kh1 Rhg8 { The a8-Rook is coming to e8 and Black has great compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
