[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #9"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/p1p1b1pp/2pP2q1/8/8/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How should Black deal with White's pawn on e7? } 12... Bh3
{ A cool intermezzo. Often I notice that intermezzos change the character of the position. Watch out for it :@@EndBracket@@! }
13. g3 Bxd6
{ Now the light squares are clearly vulnerable with the absence of White's light-squared Bishop and ...Bg4 is threatened next. }
14. Ng5 Rxf2
{ Bam! When all the pieces are perfectly placed, such fireworks are bound to happen :@@EndBracket@@! }
15. Kxf2
{ 15.Nxh3  is dubious as it allows  15...Rxh2 !  White is unable to take on h2 because of mate in 2 after   16.Kxh2  Qxg3  followed by ...Qh2#.  16.Ng5  Rh3 !  A nice geometry aiming to get the Queen to reach the g3 square.  17.Bf4   17.Nh3  of course loses to ...Qxg3+ and its mate.  17...Rxg3+  18.Bxg3  Qxg5  ∓  Finally, her highness has roared into action :@@EndBracket@@! White's position is collapsing here with the weak King. }
15... Bc5+ 16. Be3 Qxg5 { Next, the a8-Rook is coming to f8. } 17. Qd3 Rf8+ 18.
Kg1 Rf3
{ White is in danger, but he is in time to give some checks to escape from the loss. }
19. Qb3+ Kf8 20. Qb8+ Kf7 21. Qxc7+ Kg8 { And a draw. } *

