{ Find a standard positional move often seen in these kinds of endgames! }
13... a5
{ A standard expansion creating play on the queenside and White cannot really make use of the extra pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #11"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr3r/pbppb1pp/2p2q2/4N3/8/3P4/PPP1QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Which Rook to place on e8 and why? } 11... Rde8
{ Black has two options either to bring the h8-Rook or the d8-Rook to e8 to create pressure on the e-file. The text move is precise as in this particular position, Black needs the other Rook to be on h8 so that he can create some counter chances with ...h5. That's the subtle point here. }
12. Nc4 h5 { Thanks to the Black Rook on h8, this is possible. } 13. Be3 c5
{ The Bishop on b7 blazes out now and the e3-Bishop is blocked by our c5-pawn at the same time. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #12"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr3r/pbppb1pp/5q2/2p1N3/3P4/2P5/PP2QPPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Our idea is to push ...d6 but then 13.Qg4+ is in the air. How to stop it? }
12... Rhf8
{ Preparing...d6 to kick the active Knight on e5. It is a difficult move to spot and is prophylactic in nature. The point is that after ...d6, White has always Qg4+ combined with Nd7+ floating in the air. So here, with the Rook on f8, we can interpose with ...Qf5 after ...d6 when White gives a check on g4. }
13. Be3 d6 14. Qg4+
{ 14.Nd3  Qg6  15.Ne1  supporting the g2-pawn  15...Rde8  and Black's activity gives him good counterchances. }
14... Qf5 15. Qxf5+ Rxf5 16. Nd3 c4 { And Black simply fixes the queenside. }
17. Nf4 a5
{ Next, the Black King will come to d7, and once again the bishop pair serves us enough compensation. It is not easy for White to advance his pawns on either side. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #13"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppp3pp/2n5/1B1pN3/4n3/4Q3/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the best move here? } 10... O-O
{ Making use of the active and dominating Knight on e4. } 11. Bxc6
{ 11.Nxc6  If White tries to capture the pawn on c6, then its simply backfires after...  11...bxc6  12.Bxc6  Ba6 !  And the King is stuck in the center.  13.Bxa8  Rxf2  ∓  with multiple threats around the White King. }
11... Rxf2 { A supercool move, going for the throat of the King. } 12. Nd3
{ 12.Bb5  If White tries to preserve the Bishop, then it is met by  12...Rxg2  threatening...Qh4+  13.h4  White prevents ... Qh4+, but then Black has a powerful move attacking the e5-Knight by  13...Qd6  and it leads to a winning advantage. }
12... Rxg2 { The Rook on the second rank is always dangerous. } 13. Bxd5+
{ leads to forced variations, where Black tops it in the resulting consequences after... }
13... Qxd5 14. Nf4 { The key point of 13.Bxd5. } 14... Qa5+ 15. b4 Qxb4+ 16. c3
{ Finally, White can now capture the Rook on g2. With his King still stuck in the center, it looks dangerous for him. }
16... Qc4 17. Nxg2 Bg4
{ The King is cornered and with the other Rook on a8 coming to e8, it looks really scary for White as he is unable to castle. }
18. h3 Bh5 19. Nf4 Re8 { Time to bring the Rook. } 20. Nxh5 Nd6
{ And Black gets the Queen. Of course White has some pieces in turn, but the King is vulnerable and stuck in the center which gives Black the upper hand. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #14"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppp2pp/2n2n2/1B2p3/1b2P3/3Q1N2/PPPN1PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find a subtle positional move here. } 7... a5
{ Against the idea of c3-b4 advance. Black now secures the b4-Bishop and makes more space for it to breathe. }
8. O-O
{ 8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Nxe5  Qe7  10.f4  Ba6  and the two Bishops create a lot of play and especially with the Queen placed on d3, it is not advisable to go for the pawn grab here. }
8... Qe7 { Supporting the e5-pawn. } 9. Nc4 O-O 10. Bxc6
{ 10.Bg5  d6  11.Ne3  Be6  12.Bc4  h6  and Black has consolidated his position with no weaknesses. With the text move 10.Bxc6, White aims to capture the e5-pawn but we have good compensation with the bishop pair. }
10... bxc6 11. a3 Bc5 12. Ncxe5 d6 13. Nxc6 Qe8
{ Disturbing the Knight first as if we take on e4 with   13...Qxe4  then  14.Qxe4  Nxe4  15.Ne7+  and White is clearly better with the simple fact that he gets rid of the bishop pair and has an extra pawn. }
14. Ncd4 Ba6
{ One more intermezzo before taking on e4. Black is totally fine here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Training Exercises"]
[Black "Training Exercise #15"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppppb1pp/2n2n2/4p3/1PB1P3/2PQ1N2/P4PPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White prevents Black from castling. What to do? } 9... d5
{ A brilliant resource creating chaos and counterplay. } 10. Bxd5
{ 10.exd5  e4  is the point. } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5
{ 11.Qxd5  Qxd5  12.exd5  e4 !  The key counter-resource.  13.Nfd2   13.dxc6  exf3  is not going to help White in any way.  13...Ne5  the threat is ...Nd3.  14.Nxe4   14.O-O  then Black can simply support the e4-pawn by  14...Bf5  14...Bf5 =  We are two pawns down but all our pieces are springing into action and the activity clearly compensates for the pawns. }
11... Be6 { Thanks to the unprotected Queen on d3, the whole idea works. } 12.
c4 { If   12.b5  then we have  12...Bxd5  13.bxc6  e4  is the point. } 12...
Nxb4 13. Qe4 O-O
{ Sacrificing the piece to gain the initiative and the Knight on b4 will hop on to d3 instantly once White takes the piece. }
14. dxe6 Nd3+ 15. Ke2 Nc5 16. Qe3
{ 16.Qxe5  will lose to  16...Qd3+  17.Ke1  Qc2  preparing ... Nd3+ and White is busted. }
16... e4 { The e7-Bishop is coming to f6 as well now. } 17. Nfd2 Nxe6
{ The sneaky Knight eyes for the d4 and f4 squares :@@EndBracket@@, creating ruckus around White's King. }
18. Nxe4 Nf4+ { and White is forced to give her highness. } 19. Qxf4 Rxf4 20.
Bxf4
{ White has two pieces and a Rook for the Queen, but Black can immediately get one Rook back after... }
20... Bf6 21. Nbd2 Bxa1 22. Rxa1 b6
{ Three pieces vs a Queen is pretty balanced here, as the Queen is generally active. Moreover, the White King is in the center and the Queenside pawns of White are standing lonely and disorganized. }
*

